<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government Hopes to Bridge Gap With Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Foreign Minister Mustafa
Osman Ismail Wednesday expressed hope that the coming round of
talks with the opposition Sudanese People's Liberation Army (SPLA)
would help bridge their gap.
</P>
<P>
The fresh round of talks between the SPLA, the leading rebel
faction in southern Sudan, and the government will be held in
Kenyan capital Nairobi next month, Ismail told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of the planned talks despite the
failed previous negotiations in Nairobi and Addis Ababa due to the
insistence of SPLA leader John Garang on carving up south Sudan to
establish a confederation which the government opposes strongly.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Presidential Adviser for Peace Nafe' Ali Nafe' said
the government prefers dialog to establish peace with the
northern opposition forces and the south's SPLA as well.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing fighting in south Sudan was mainly caused by
Garang's intransigence, he said, adding that the signing of a
peace accord with the SPLA would establish peace in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA waged a separatist war against the Sudanese government
in 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
