<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNEP Chief Appeals to Combat Desertification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Klaus Toepfer, Executive Director
of the United Nations Environment Program (UNEP) has appealed for
the global efforts to combat desertification and drought for the
lives of the people inhabiting the world's dry lands
</P>
<P>
In his message released here Wednesday to mark the World Day to
Combat Desertification, which is observed annually on June 17, he
said the day serves to strengthen the global effort to face the
challenges of desertification in all the regions of the world.
</P>
<P>
He noted that UNEP's environmental concerns are in broad terms
such as ozone depletion, extinction of biodiversity, climate
change and loss of soil fertility.
</P>
<P>
These environmental issues touch the lives of millions of
people around the world, and impact disproportionately on the
poor and the vulnerable, he said.
</P>
<P>
Toepfer pointed out that the degradation of a particular
rangeland or soil erosion on farmland or the progressive
shortening of fallow, directly affects the poor because they are
directly related to household food security.
</P>
<P>
In their quest for food security, Toepfer said, the poor
inhabiting the ecologically fragile dry lands have to overuse the
limited resources available to them. As a result, environmental
degradation imposes further constraints on their livelihood in a
"vicious circle".
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the effects of desertification are
manifested socially. Land degradation directly affects the poor
who are not involved in decision-making and planning which
influence their lives.
</P>
<P>
Prevention and control of desertification requires much more
than money, he said, adding the science and technology are
fundamental to an improved management of the dry lands.
</P>
<P>
He also noted the Convention to Combat Desertification is the
first international treaty to squarely address poverty and
environmental degradation in rural areas, with the aim to benefit
the hundreds of millions of predominantly poor and food-insecure
people.
</P>
<P>
Toepfer pledged that UNEP would continue to work toward
strengthening the implementation of the convention and reinforce
partnerships with other U.N. agencies, community organizations
and even individuals worldwide to fight the menace of
desertification. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
