<HEADLINE> One Third of World Refugees in Africa: UNHCR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) said Wednesday that as of
January 1999, there were 6.5 million people of concern to it in
Africa, out of an estimated 21.1 million worldwide.
</P>
<P>
In its June issue of "Africa fact Sheet", the UNHCR said the
Africa figure includes 3.3 million refugees, 2.1 million
internally displaced and 1.1 million former refugees who have
recently returned home.
</P>
<P>
In January 1998, the global number of people concerning to
UNHCR was 22. 3 million, of whom 7.2 million were in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR announced that the top five African refugee countries
of origin are Sierra Leone, with 410,900, Somalia, with 401,300,
Sudan, with 372,900, Eritrea, with 342,300 and Burundi with
299,400.
</P>
<P>
It also announced that the top four refugee-hosting countries
in Africa are Guinea , Sudan, Tanzania and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
However, UNHCR said the above figures do not include 200,000
Burundians who have been in Tanzania since 1970's and who are not
assisted by the UNHCR.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR said among the 10 largest refugees return movements
in 1998, seven were related to African countries. These were:
235,700 returned to Liberia; 193,800 to Sierra Leone; 62,400 to
the Democratic Republic of Congo; Somalia with 48,100 returnees,
Mali with 27,000, Burundi with 23,600 and Angola, with 21,800.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
