<HEADLINE> World Bank Supports AIDS Control in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- India will embark on the second
phase of its fight against HIV/AIDS with the help of an
International Development Association (IDA) credit totaling 191
million U.S. dollars approved by the World Bank, the bank
announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Second National HIV/AIDS Control Project will provide
further momentum to the country's ongoing program to reduce the
rate of growth of the HIV infection and strengthen the country's
capacity to respond to the epidemic, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Over the last 18 months, the Indian government has dramatically
increased the scope of its HIV/AIDS control activities by adopting
a new National Policy Document; engaging public, private, and
voluntary sectors in the preparation of plans; moving
implementation of services to states and municipal corporations;
and completing a baseline survey of HIV prevalence.
</P>
<P>
According to the National AIDS Control Organization, India has
more than 4 million HIV-infected people. By early in the next
century, India will have the highest number of AIDS cases in the
world. Even if HIV infection reaches a "low" level of five percent
seen in many other countries, more than 37 million Indians would
be HIV infected.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank said that global experience with HIV/AIDS and
other sexually transmitted infections (STI) demonstrates that the
most effective strategy to prevent an epidemic is to intervene
quickly among the groups at high risk for contracting and
spreading HIV.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the most important component of the project focuses
on high risk groups -- commercial sex workers, truck drivers,
migrant laborers, men having sex with men, and injecting drug
users -- by providing peer counseling, condon promotion, treatment
of STIs, and client programs.
</P>
<P>
The total costs of the project are 229 million dollars to which
the Indian government will contribute 38.8 million dollars. The
interest-free IDA credit is provided on standard IDA terms with 35
years to maturity and 10 years grace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
