<HEADLINE> Palestinians Serious About Peacemaking: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak will meet in Washington in December to prepare for the
final status talks between the Palestinians and Israel, a top
Palestinian official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians "are serious about peacemaking" and hope to
make progress in the peace talks with the Israelis, Palestinian
Minister of Planning and International Cooperation Nabil Shaath
told Egypt's Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said the Palestinians' priority is to "achieve tangible
progress in negotiations (with Israel) that will lead to declaring
an independent Palestinian state."
</P>
<P>
Shaath said the Palestinian National Authority "will pursue
contacts with the United States, European Union states and other
friendly countries" for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Shaath arrived in Cairo on Sunday to take part in a two-day
United Nations conference on maintaining rights for the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the Palestinians did have plans to declare a
state in case the hard-line Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu won last month's elections.
</P>
<P>
Had Netanyahu won, "a Palestinian state would have been
declared immediately," MENA quoted Shaath as saying.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was defeated by the moderate Labor Party leader Ehud
Barak in the May 17 Israeli elections. Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat postponed plans to declare statehood last month to avoid
influencing the elections.
</P>
<P>
Barak has said he will make the resumption of peace talks with
the Palestinians a top priority, following three years of deadlock
under his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
Shaath called on Barak to show goodwill and earnestness,
implement the Wye interim peace accord, halt settlement activities
and judaization of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinians will not give up anything for nothing," he
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
