<HEADLINE> Iraqi Civilian Injured in U.S. Warplanes Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 16 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi civilian was injured on
Wednesday in U.S. and British warplanes' attacks on civilian
facilities in southern Iraq, an Iraqi military spokesman
announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was quoted by the Iraqi News Agency as saying
that at 16:30 (1230 GMT), 23 formations of enemy warplanes coming
from Saudi and Kuwaiti airspace violated southern Iraqi airspace
over Thi-Qar, Basra, Misan, Qadisiya and Najaf provinces.
</P>
<P>
The enemy planes bombed civilian facilities in the region,
injuring one civilian, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He added that Iraqi air defenses fired back and forced
the enemy planes to flee to their bases in Saudi Arabia and
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Ten formations coming from Turkish air space violated Iraqi
airspace at 10:42 (0642 GMT) over Dohuk, Erbil and Neineva
provinces, said the spokesman, adding that Iraqi anti-aircraft
units repulsed the enemy planes.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.S. and Britain launched airstrikes against Iraq
last December, their warplanes have made 1,639 sorties over the
so-called northern no-fly zone and 6,847 sorties over the
so-called southern no-fly zone, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones in
Iraq following the 1991 Gulf War with a claimed aim of
protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims from
possible attacks by the Iraqi troops.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's four-night bombardment of Iraqi targets,
U.S. and British warplanes have been regularly attacking Iraqi
civilian and military targets, causing severe civilian casualties
and property damages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
