<HEADLINE> GCC to Set up Committee for Power Grid Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 16 (Xinhua) -- An independent committee to
manage a power grid linkage project among the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) member state was set up Wednesday in Riyadh, Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Five states of the six-member GCC, namely, Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait, Qatar, the United Arab Emirate (UAE) and Bahrain, signed
an agreement to this effect Wednesday after a one-day electricity
ministerial meeting, the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Oman is the only exception due to its local technical
reasons. Muscat said it has yet to finish the linkage of its own
power networks.
</P>
<P>
The proposed authority, which will be based in eastern Saudi
region, will manage and supervise the link-up project approved by
GCC leaders during their 1997 summit in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The project, designed to exchange the reserves of energy
available in the Gulf, was estimated to cost 1.1 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to a related agreement reached by GCC electricity
ministers last March, each member state should pay 5 percent of
its share in the first phase of the project. But it didn't mention
the specific amount each state should pay.
</P>
<P>
The first stage involves Bahrain, Kuwait, Qatar and Saudi
Arabia, and the second covers Oman and the UAE.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the project was expected to be completed in
three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
