<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Accuses G-8 of Involving in Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Ministry Deputy
Spokesman Sermet Atacanli said here Wednesday that Turkey
disapproves of the G-8 countries' initiative regarding the Cyprus
issue.
</P>
<P>
Atacanli told reporters that the initiative constituted an
interference in the United Nations goodwill mission on the
long-divided island.
</P>
<P>
"I should underline that we do not approve the G-8 countries'
arbitrary interference in this issue," Atacanli said.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to a June 10 statement by the group's foreign
ministers, which calls for an immediate resumption of the dialog
between the two Cypriot sides with no preconditions, and their
upcoming summit in Cologne, where the Cyprus issue will be again
on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Atacanli stressed that the efforts of the G-8 contradicted the
goodwill mission carried out by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
and his Cyprus envoys.
</P>
<P>
He said that "the June 10 statement of the G-8s will not bring
about any acceleration in the solution process and it contains
contradictions within itself."
</P>
<P>
The G-8s do not have the authority to call on the two sides to
restart dialog, Atacanli pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He added that the proposal of Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktas for the establishment of a confederation has the full
support of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"Any talks in Cyprus can be held only between the two
sovereign states. There cannot be any talks between communities,"
Atacanli said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
