<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African States Meet on AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A southern African conference on
the prevention and fight against AIDS Wednesday called on all
African countries to map out plans to reduce the incidents of the
deadly disease among them.
</P>
<P>
A document issued at the end of the three-day conference here
suggested actions be taken by African countries to cut one fourth
of the HIV infected cases among youths between 15 and 24 years
before 2005, in most highly infectious African countries.
</P>
<P>
The document also urged countries on the continent to make sure
that at least 90 percent of the youths in this age group know how
to prevent themselves from contracting AIDS and that half of the
HIV-positive pregnant women get access to medical examination,
consultation and treatment.
</P>
<P>
Joint action and coordination were also urged at the meeting in
order to wage a more effective campaign against AIDS in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The annual expenditure in fighting against AIDS in Africa
should be doubled to reach 300 million U.S. dollars next year,
from the present 150 million, the document said.
</P>
<P>
There are over 20 million AIDs patients in Africa, while two
million died of the disease last year, with half a million being
children.
</P>
<P>
Nine southern African countries were represented at the AIDS
conference which was financed by the United Nations joint program
on AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
