<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Tomb Discovered in South of Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A joint Egyptian-Australian
archaeological team has discovered an important tomb dating back
to the Early Dynasties Era some 4,500 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The team, excavating in the area of Helwan to the south of
Cairo, found that the stepped tomb was carved out of a rock,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Gaballah Ali Gaballah, secretary general of Egypt's Supreme
Antiquities Council, was quoted by the news agency as saying the
tomb is believed to belong to the nobility of the Second Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
It has two halls, Gaballah said, adding that there are two
burial chambers on either side of one hall and six chambers along
the other.
</P>
<P>
The joint team also discovered a deep hole carved in the rock,
which was probably designed as a burial place, with large numbers
of broken pottery pieces and a small headless clay statue of a man
with his hands tied behind his back, believed to be a captive.
</P>
<P>
The team further found in the same area a raised platform of
adobe bedecked on its outer wall with figurative designs and
believed to have been used for storing utensils and pottery pieces.
</P>
<P>
Human skeletons and the remains of a clay coffin were also
discovered nearby. 
</P>
</TEXT>
