<HEADLINE> Europe's Markets Jump on Subdued US Inflation Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON June 16 (Xinhua) - European stock markets moved higher
in late trading Wednesday after inflation in the United States
turned out to be lower than expected.
</P>
<P>
Britain's benchmark FTSE 100 advanced 0.8 percent, or 53.7
points, to 6504.9 on the strength of a triple-digit surge in the
Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
The good inflation figures helped boost the financial sector,
led by Barclays, which announced that its business had got off to
a good start in 1999. The bank sector accounted for 32 points of
the blue chip advance.
</P>
<P>
Railtrack climbed 7.1 percent, and was the top gainer among
FTSE 100 stocks, on continued positive reaction to Tuesday's news
of a government invitation to exclusive talks for the group to
link sub-surface lines to the railway.
</P>
<P>
Germany's benchmark Xetra Dax was up 37.71 points at 5382.66, a
gain of 0.7 percent. Shares in software maker SAP soared 8 percent
after better-than-expected results from US software house Oracle.
</P>
<P>
The US data sent Paris stocks on the CAC 40 index roaring up
1.4 percent, or 63.57 points, to end at 4481.75, elbowing past the
previous closing record of 4442.84, set on May 3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
