<HEADLINE> Minister Warns of Humanitarian Catastrophe in Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian Emergency Situations
Minister Sergei Shoigu said Wednesday that Yugoslavia might soon
face a widespread humanitarian catastrophe with the high
concentration of refugees and increasingly hot weather.
</P>
<P>
The minister, who returned to Moscow from a trip to Belgrade,
said water purification and supply system has been virtually
destroyed in NATO bombings, which may lead to epidemics.
</P>
<P>
Shoigu said that 700,000 refugees from Bosnia and Herzegovina
in Yugoslavia have been joined by some 50,000 people from Kosovo,
adding that he saw a column of refugees from Kosovo 30 kilometers
long.
</P>
<P>
"They were not only Serbs but also Romanians, Gypsies and
members of other ethnic groups," the Interfax news agency quoted
the minister as saying in a television interview.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Shoigu said, lack of fuel could well result in the
loss of this year's harvest.
</P>
<P>
With the power system destroyed in the NATO air attacks, many
hospitals and other social services and institutions cannot
function properly.
</P>
<P>
The minister said Yugoslavia has only a few months to restore
its power system and oil refineries before cold weather sets in.
</P>
</TEXT>
