<HEADLINE> Schroeder: Cologne Summit Should Give World Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 16 (Xinhua)--The upcoming Cologne summit of the
seven industrial nations (G-7) will give the world economy a clear
signal for a new booming stage, German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder told his parliament on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a speech entitled "Design the Globalization Together",
Schroeder expected a world economy growth rate of 3.4 per cent in
next year as a consequence of the summit.
</P>
<P>
State or government chiefs of Britain, France, Italy, Canada,
Japan and the United States are expected to attend the summit
chaired by Schroeder from June 18 to 20.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Jeltsin is due to arrive in Cologne on
Sunday. And he will meet with the G-7 leaders separately under the
Group of Eight(G-8), namely the G-7 plus Russia.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder set four "equally important strategic goals" that
must be achieved in the age of globalization, including economic
competitiveness, social equity, environmental endurability, and
constitutional democracy.
</P>
<P>
"These four goals will make up the magic square of the
modernization in the next century," he said.
</P>
<P>
Amid the current weakness of European economy, Schroeder
foresaw a revival in next year, saying a better interest rate
policy of the Eurolands would help pushing their economy at a
growth rate of 2.9 per cent.
</P>
<P>
The Chancellor's optimism was ironically criticized by the
opposition leaders, who said Schroeder had done little to solve
Germany's unemployment since he governed the country.
</P>
<P>
"That... is something like The New Clothe for The Emperor,"
commented Wolfgang Schaeuble, chairman of the main opposition
Christian Democratic Union (CDU). 
</P>
</TEXT>
