<HEADLINE> EU to Offer Angola 10 Million Euro in Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Union representative
in Angola, Cons des Rueal, announced here Wednesday that the EU
Commission decided to offer Angola 10 million euro (about 11
million U.S. dollars) in emergency humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
The aid will be used to "cover the Angolan people's urgent
needs," and the priority will be given to the war refugees and to
provide them with basic food, health products and medicines, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The EU representative noted that due to lack of security, the
current aid could only benefit the residents in "accessible"
regions. Besides, he added, the cost of humanitarian actions will
be increased remarkably since most resources will be airlifted.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Angolan government indicate that the number
of refugees in the country has reached 1.7 million since the
civil war was renewed in the southern African country at the end
of last year.
</P>
<P>
In central Angola's Huambo and Bie provinces where fighting
between the government army and the rebel National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola is the most fierce, many cities have
been besieged, leaving the residents there to fend for themselves
with not even the basic livelihood secured.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to the Angola News Agency, Portuguese
ambassador in Luanda announced here Wednesday that his government
will donate 500 tons of rice (which is worth of 300,000 U.S.
dollars) to Angola, its former colony, to aid the refugees in
central Angola's Benguela, Huambo, and Kwanza-sul provinces.
</P>
</TEXT>
