<HEADLINE> First Shipment of Saudi Foodstuff Reaches Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The first shipment of foodstuff
from Saudi Arabia under the oil-for-food program has arrived in Um
Qasr Port in the southern Iraqi province of Basra, an official
source at the Iraqi Trade Ministry said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The total value of contracts Iraq has signed with Saudi
companies for the purchase of foodstuff, prerequisites of
agricultural production and some oil equipment reaches 150 million
U.S. dollars, the unnamed source was quoted by the Iraqi News
Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The sixth phase of the oil-for-food program, which came into
force on May 25, allows Iraq to export 5.2 billion dollars worth
of oil in six months to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian
supplies for its 22 million people.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi-Saudi relations have been cool since the 1991 Gulf
War touched off by Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has long accused the Saudi government of providing
logistic support to U.S. and British warplanes taking off from
its bases and patrolling a no-fly zone over southern Iraqi
airspace and thus making it a key partner in aggression against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the southern no-fly zone
in Iraq in 1992 with a claimed aim of protecting the Shiite
Muslims there from any possible attacks by the Iraqi troops.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.S. and Britain launched four-night airstrikes
against Iraq last December, their warplanes taking off from
Saudi, Kuwaiti and Turkish bases have been regularly attacking
Iraqi targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
