<HEADLINE> Annan to Appoint Commission to Monitor East Timor Ballot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said on Wednesday that he would soon appoint an independent
electoral commission to monitor the East Timor ballot
ascertaining its future.
</P>
<P>
In a video-message to the people of East Timor, Annan said the
commission "will be the final authority on electoral justice and
will ensure the transparency and impartiality of all procedures
and decisions".
</P>
<P>
East Timor, with an area of nearly 19,000 square kilometers and
a population of 800,000, is defined by the U.N. General Assembly
as one of the 17 non-self-governing territories remaining in the
world.
</P>
<P>
It had been a Portuguese colony until 1975 when Indonesia
occupied it following an internal rift. Jakarta annexed it in 1976
and since then the U.N. has been trying to find a solution to the
issue.
</P>
<P>
Talks between Indonesia and Portugal under the U.N. mediation
resulted in an agreement on May 5 this year that a direct ballot
be held on August 8 to determine whether East Timorese will choose
special autonomy or independence.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Secretary-General was charged by the agreement with
setting up a U.N. mission to organize and conduct the ballot.
Annan said the mission will comprise some 900 international
personnel.
</P>
<P>
In the message, Annan said the U.N. is neither for or against
any result and that the ballot is not about winning or losing a
competition, rather a chance for the East Timorese to settle the
question peacefully and an opportunity to launch a new era of
reconciliation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
