<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Deri's Exit Paves Way for Shas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 16 (Xinhua)-- The Council of Torah Sages of
Shas, one of Israel's major political parties, on Wednesday
announced its painful decision to accept Aryeh Deri's resignation
as head of the party.
</P>
<P>
The four-member council headed by Shas spiritual leader Rabbi
Ovadia Yosef also announced that the council will not appoint
a new party leader until Deri's case is settled by the High
Court of Justice.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Deri's resignation will surely produce
repercussions across the country's political spectrum as it has
not only paved the way for Shas to join an emerging coalition to
be headed by Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak, but also has made it
possible for Barak to shape the coalition into a broad-based one.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the country's proportional direct election law, 15
political parties have been elected into the current 15th Knesset
(parliament) during the elections, causing tremendous trouble for
Barak to form the coalition as they have raised so many demands.
</P>
<P>
Shas won 17 Knesset seats in the elections and turned out to be
the third largest party just behind Barak's One Israel and the
Likud headed by the outgoing Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu. But One Israel's sister party Meretz, which helped
Barak win the elections, refused to accept Shas to join the
coalition, citing Deri's fraud and bribe-taking acts in the past.
</P>
<P>
After Deri's resignation, there will be no reason for
Meretz to continue opposing Shas's inclusion into the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Apparently delighted by Deri's resignation, Barak announced
Tuesday night to halt the coalition talks for 24 hours, giving
Shas more time to settle the Deri case and decide whether to join
the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said, Deri's resignation has pushed Barak onto and
advantageous position.
</P>
<P>
With Shas's 17 Knesset seats in hand, Barak has nothing to
worry about the unreasonable demands raised by some other small
parties. This could help him speed up the coalition talks and
form the new government at an earlier date.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, based on the progress in the coalition talks, Barak
is set to form a broad-based coalition which occupy over 70
Knesset seats, enough to maintain the government's stability.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, Shas is an orthodox religious party in Israel, but
it adopts a moderate policy in handling with political affairs.
Shas's inclusion into the coalition will help One Israel to
formulate policies concerning peace talks and move the Middle
East peace process forward more easily. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
