<HEADLINE> Lebanese Government Urged to Investigate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A total of 24 Lebanese lawmakers
Wednesday urged the government to conduct an inquiry to determine
the identity of the mastermind behind the scathing diatribe
against former Prime Minister Rafik Hariri through the official
National News Agency (NNA).
</P>
<P>
Deputy Hussein Yatim submitted the request which was signed by
24 deputies, most of them from the two parliamentary blocks of
Hariri and another leading opposition leader Walid Jumblatt.
</P>
<P>
They asked the government of Salim Hoss to answer who in deed
launched the smear campaign, a move decried by politicians as a
blow to the transparency preached by the current administration.
</P>
<P>
Late Tuesday night, a two-page statement was faxed to leading
news organizations in the country from unknown sources and
published in the late edition of the NNA.
</P>
<P>
The statement accused Hariri of seeking to undermine Lebanon's
political and economic stability, sabotaging Lebanon's alliance
with Syria in the U.S.-sponsored Arab-Israeli peace talks, and of
having an "overlap of interests" with the assassins who killed
four judges in his hometown of Sidon last week.
</P>
<P>
The accusations, attributed to "government sources," also
lambasted Hariri's domestic conduct, claiming that his
high-profile appearance at the Luciano Pavarotti concert Saturday,
and an ensuing stroll with his family through the Flea Market in
downtown Beirut, displayed insensitivity toward the slain judges.
</P>
<P>
The anonymous charges caused sharp reaction and uproar across
the country's political spectrum. Many politicians think it is a
non-democratic, impermissible and unacceptable practice in the
state of law to wage attack on ex-premier through the independent
state-run media.
</P>
<P>
Hoss, Hariri's long time political foe, was quick to deny he
was involved in the anonymous statement, saying that is not his
style, while Harri remained tight-lipped on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The tirade broke a three-month ceasefire brokered by Syria
between the former prime minister and the current regime of
President Emile Lahoud.
</P>
<P>
Syria is the main power broker in Lebanon with 35,000 troops
stationed across the country as peacekeepers to prevent the
rekindling of the 1975-1990 civil war.
</P>
<P>
Press reports predicted that Syria was expected to step in
soon to reconcile the Lahoud-Hoss dyarchy with Hariri
again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
