<HEADLINE> Somali Refugees in Ethiopia Heading Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A total of 900 Somali refugees
have been repatriated Wednesday from eastern Ethiopia to northwest
Somalia, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)
said.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua here, UNHCR Addis Ababa office
press official Mahary Michow said this was the second batch of
repatriated Somali refugees since their repatriation from eastern
Ethiopia to northwest Somalia restarted on Monday or June 14,
1999.
</P>
<P>
Mahary said 689 Somali refugees went home on that date alone.
</P>
<P>
He said the 1999 operation began from Hartisheik camp in
northeast Ethiopia where 10,000 Somali refugees are expected to be
repatriated, adding that following is another 10,000 Somalis in
six other sites.
</P>
<P>
There will be three movements per week -- on Monday, Wednesday
and Saturday, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation operation was agreed in March this year
between UNHCR and officials in northwestern Somalia, he added.
</P>
<P>
Almost 60,000 Somali refugees had gone home from camps in
Ethiopia from late 1997 to November 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
