<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moscow Calls for Disarming Kosovo KLA Militants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, June 16 (Xinhua) - Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov said on Wednesday that the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA)
should be disarmed "as soon as possible".
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival here, Ivanov told reporters that "the KLA must
be demilitarized as provided for in the U.N. resolution" on
solving the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
"This is an obligation for the international force in Kosovo
which must take care of this as soon as possible. Otherwise, there
will be big problems very soon and the peace settlement in Kosovo
will be under threat," he said.
</P>
<P>
"That is why we call on all our partners to carefully respect
the U.N. resolution's wording on dealing with the KLA's
demilitarization," said Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov, who is due to hold talks with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright on Thursday, said that Moscow would like to
remove all kind of differences ahead of a meeting scheduled for
Sunday between Bill Clinton and Boris Yeltsin at the Group of
Eight summit in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev and U.S.
Defense Secretary William Cohen have started their talks on
Wednesday to solve a dispute between the two countries over Russia
's peacekeeping role in the war-battered Yugoslav province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Before the talks, Sergeyev told reporters that all differences
over Russia's advance troops in Kosovo had been eliminated in the
negotiations between Russian and NATO officers and it was
unnecessary for the West to be worried over the presence of the
Russian troops in Pristina, capital of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Cohen has declared in Washington that the talks on options for
Russia's part in Kosovo peacekeeping had made much headway and the
United States would study the options in line with the two basic
principles: a unified command and no separate sector for Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
