<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Formally Declares for Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore
formally kicked off his campaign for president Wednesday in his
home state of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to a hometown crowd of about 3,000 people, Gore
promised moral leadership to solve "the crisis in the American
family."
</P>
<P>
"With your help, I will take my own values and faith and family
to the presidency -- to build an America that is not only better
off, but better," he said.
</P>
<P>
"And that is why today, I announce that I am a candidate for
the president of the United States," he said.
</P>
<P>
Using phrases like "moral leadership" and "values and faith and
family," Gore appears to be distancing himself from Clinton's
character questions to show he can stand on his own as a
presidential figure, political observers said.
</P>
<P>
"Seven years ago, we needed to put America back to work, and we
did," the vice president said. "Now we must build on that
foundation. We must make family life work in America."
</P>
<P>
"The crisis in the American family today knows no boundary of
class or race," Gore said.
</P>
<P>
Gore is only facing challenge from former New Jersey Senator
Bill Bradly for the Democratic Party's presidential nomination,
but his campaign seemed to start in the shadow of Texas Governor
George W. Bush, the Republican front-runner who leads in polls for
months.
</P>
<P>
But Gore said polls taken so far before the November 2000
presidential election were meaningless. He said "instead of 18
months before the election maybe 18 days" is when people should
pay attention to polls.
</P>
<P>
Gore, 51, a Vietnam veteran, is running for U.S. president for
the second time. He is a former journalist, House member and U.S.
Senator.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
