<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Reshuffles Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Saudi King Fahd Ibn
Abdul-Aziz Wednesday announced a cabinet reshuffle, the second
one in nearly 25 years, with no changes in key ministries.
</P>
<P>
Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz, who has been in
charge of the day-to-day affairs of the kingdom since his
ailing half brother King Fahd suffered a stroke in 1995,
retained his post as deputy prime minister and chief of the
national guards.
</P>
<P>
Former foreign, defense and interior ministers, all senior
princes of the ruling Al-Saud family, also remained in their
offices in the newly-formed 23-member cabinet, the Kuwait News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
There has been no change either in the oil and finance
ministries, also two-key portfolios in the world's largest oil
producing and exporting country.
</P>
<P>
Those who lost their posts in the new cabinet are former
Minister of Islamic Endowments Abdullah al-Turki and Minister of
Pilgrimage Affairs Mahmoud Safar. They are replaced by Saleh
Abdul-Aziz Al-Sheikh and Iyad Ibn Amin Yemeni respectively.
</P>
<P>
Khalid Al-Qosaibi took over as planning minister, while
former Labor and Social Affairs Minister Musaid Al-Sanani left
in favor of Ali Al-Namla.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Al-Fayez, who was chairing the Civil Service
Institution, took the portfolio of the newly-established Civil
Service Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The former Saudi government was formed in 1995 in the
first cabinet shakeup since 1975. 
</P>
</TEXT>
