<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Puts Its Insurance Market In Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Remarkable achievements have been
realized in China's efforts to put its insurance market in order
since the beginning of the year, according to Ma Yongwei vice-
chairman of the China Insurance Regulatory Commission (CIRC).
</P>
<P>
In a press release here today, Ma said the watchdog's
strengthened supervision over the market's behavior and risk
management of insurers has led to the healthy development of the
sector.
</P>
<P>
According to CIRC figures, the sector recorded a total premium
income of 52.9 billion yuan in the first five months of the year,
up 7.79 percent on a yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
This includes a premium income of 31.28 billion yuan from life
insurance and 21.62 billion yuan from property insurance, up 11.07
percent and 3.06 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The insurers paid out 17.29 billion yuan in indemnities, a rise
of 0.34 percent over the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to properly control the market, the CIRC has
introduced unified policies for vehicle and aviation accident
insurance, hence preventing the misuse of fake policies and unfair
competition by kick-backs and the expansion of liabilities.
</P>
<P>
The CIRC also launched a crackdown on illegal brokerage
activities, including suspending the British-funded Sedgwick
Insurance &AMP; Risk Management Consultants (China) Limited for
unlicensed brokerage business.
</P>
<P>
The release said most of the representative offices of foreign
insurance companies in China have now stopped their brokerage
business activities.
</P>
<P>
The watchdog also stepped up its annual inspection and
supervision of the daily activities of insurance firms, including
their business expansion, management and existing financial
situation.
</P>
<P>
A number of companies found to have been practicing improper
activities were duly punished. Among them are local branches of
the China Pacific Insurance company and the Huatai insurance firm
and the People's Insurance Corporation of China.
</P>
<P>
To provide a solid base for the rule of law in the insurance
market, the CIRC has issued a number of regulations concerning the
operation of the watchdog itself, set down the required
qualifications for senior managers of insurance firms and rules
for the administration of overseas-funded insurance firms.
</P>
<P>
Ma Yongwei noted that though there has been a remarkable
improvement more has to be done in the remaining months of the
year, particularly in the supervision of the market by the
watchdog and the prevention of risks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
