<HEADLINE> Pakistani Forces Not Crossed into Indian-Held Kashmir: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz
said here Wednesday that Pakistani forces have not crossed into
India-held Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Kashmiris are struggling for their right of self-determination,
Aziz told the media while commenting on U.S. President Bill
Clinton's demand for the withdrawal of Pakistani forces from
Kargil on the Line of Control (LoC) in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Media reports here said Wednesday that Clinton, in his
telephonic talks Tuesday night with Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif,
asked Pakistan to withdraw the Kashmiri militants and its troops
from India-held Kashmir to defuse the tension on LoC.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said Kashmiri freedom fighters are not in Pakistan's
control and Pakistan could not impose its decisions on them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Pakistan's army spokesman Brig. Rashid Qureshi told
the press that Pakistan is closely monitoring movement of the
Indian troops along the LoC.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the situation on LoC, he said Indian troops
continue to shell areas on Pakistan's side of the LoC and
Pakistani troops retaliate strongly.
</P>
<P>
Indian artillery shells fell four to five kilometers deep into
the Pakistani side of the LoC. However, there was no damage or
casualties, the spokesman said. 
</P>
