<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 200,000 Tanzanians Suffering from Eye Diseases: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- An African doctor has warned
that Tanzania should take measures to cure eye diseases for
people, otherwise the number of the blind in the country will be
more than doubled in two decades.
</P>
<P>
A workshop held recently in the northern town of Moshi revealed
that some 200,000 Tanzanians are suffering from blindness because
of the prevalence of cataract, trachoma, corneal disease,
glaucoma, and deficiency in vitamin A, The Guardian reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
If the situation is not contained, the number will rise to
450,000 by the year 2025, said David Yorston, an eye specialist at
Kenya's Kikuyu hospital.
</P>
<P>
Presenting a paper at the workshop on Community Eye Care,
Yorston said the blindness of people means a loss of 26 million
U.S. dollars in production to the country, a situation which could
be controlled by improving nutrition of children and pregnant
women.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the same workshop, Prof. John Shao, the
vice-chancellor of the Tumaini University, advised African
institutions and communities to improve the quality of their
services to minimize eye-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
The professor, who is also director of the Kilimanjaro
Christian Medical Center, stressed the need of training
practitioners with necessary knowledge, skills and attitude in
treating patients with eye diseases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
