<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Travellers' Cheque to Be Formerly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Formal circulation of the
travellers' cheque of the Economic Community for West African
States (ECOWAS) will begin on July 1 in all 16 member states of
the community.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in capital Abuja Tuesday, the ECOWAS
secretariat said the choice of that day was made at a recent
extraordinary meeting of the Committee of Governors of ECOWAS
Central Banks in Cairo, Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The travellers' cheque which would be in denominations of five,
10, 20, 50 and 100 West African Units of Account (WAUA) was
introduced to enhance regional trade, tourism and integration, The
Guardian newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement said commercial banks and operators of bureaux de
change were charged with buying and selling of the cheque to the
public and organizations.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS travellers' cheque was officially launched in
Nigeria's capital of Abuja last October during the 21st ECOWAS
summit. One WAUA is equivalent to 1.35 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
