<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Economic Delegation to Visit Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Iranian economic and
industrial delegation is due in Cairo in early July to seek
business opportunities in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will include representatives of the Iranian
Company for External Investments and Iranian members in the Board
of Directors of the Egypt-Iran Weaving and Spinning Company based
in Suez, 120 kilometers east of Cairo, the Middle East News Agency
(MENA) reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The planned visit of the delegation constitutes a further sign
of the improving ties between Egypt and Iran.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries were severed after Egypt
signed in 1979 a peace treaty Israel, which Iran regards as its
arch enemy in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, especially after moderate Iranian
President Mohammad Khatami came to power in August 1997, the two
countries have often exchanged visits by senior officials,
economic and cultural delegations in a bid to thaw out the
relations.
</P>
<P>
The Iranians will study the possibility of investing in
industrial development projects in the free zone area north of the
Gulf of Suez, the news agency added.
</P>
<P>
The group will also discuss setting up a huge weaving and
spinning complex by the Egypt-Iran Company, MENA quoted
Abdel-Hakim Hagag, head of the company, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will invest 300 million Egyptian pounds (88.24 million
U.S. dollars) for the complex and Iran will put up 100 million
pounds (29.41 million dollars), Hagag said.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, due to begin in the first week of July, the
two sides will study the financing of expansions in the Egypt-Iran
Company. Some 50 million dollars are expected to be invested in
the company, MENA added.
</P>
<P>
Iran has invested 220 million pounds (64.7 million dollars) in
seven projects of weaving, carpets, ready-made garments and banks
in Egypt. The two countries' trade volume stood at 75 million
dollars in 1997, with Egypt's imports amounting to 35 million
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
