<HEADLINE> Crowds Believe Mbeki Will Boost Jobs, Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRETORIA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- South Africans attending a
"people's concert" in celebration of Thabo Mbeki's inauguration as
president, appeared to share a belief that their new leader would
speed up job creation and boost economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"I think that changes promised by the African National Congress
will be sped up by Thabo Mbeki," said 44-year-old Dintoe Taunyane,
echoing the view of most people interviewed Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that as an economist, he has all the skills needed
to improve our economic situation."
</P>
<P>
Taunyane's wife Janet, 41, said she believed Mbeki would tackle
issues close to the hearts of young people, as he himself was a
young man.
</P>
<P>
July Skosana, 22, said he had confidence in the new president,
"because he has a lot of experience", while Bongani Mkhatshwa, 29,
said: "I like him because he will do good things".
</P>
<P>
"I like him, he will make everything better," said 54-year-old
Mirriam Vilakazi, while Mary Mokolo, 32, said: "I am happy --
maybe I will now get everything I need -- work, food...
everything."
</P>
<P>
Most of the concert-goers said they were sad about the
departure of Mbeki's predecessor Nelson Mandela, but believed he
should have some time to himself.
</P>
<P>
"He is old and he needs to rest," said Numsa Twala, 19.
</P>
<P>
South Africans travelled from as far as Thaba Nchu, Thohoyandou
and Groblersdal to attend Wednesday's celebrations, which kicked
off shortly after 1:00 p.m. with speeches by Mbeki and Mandela.
</P>
<P>
More than 50,000 people attended the event.
</P>
<P>
They were shuttled to the Union Buildings from 7:00 a.m. by
about 100 buses from six depots in and around Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Artists expected to perform include South African stars Brenda
Fassie, Johannes Kerkorrel, Lucky Dube, Johnny Clegg and Juluka,
and African performers such as Youssou N'dour and Angelique Kidjo.
 
