<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Intensifying Effort Against Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government is
intensifying its effort against terrorist activities in the
country to make sure everyone is living in safety.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Minister of Security Muruli Mukasa at a
press conference here at the International Conference Center
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said various security agencies in the country had launched a
joint operation on May 3 of 1999 and a total of 77 terrorist
coordinators have been netted so far in various parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 13 of them have already appeared before courts of
law, he added.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, the exhibits include 13 rifles, three
pistols, one U.S.-made sub-machine gun, one bomb, some grenades,
1,657 rounds of live bullets as well as military fatigues.
</P>
<P>
A government soldier was arrested in the eastern district of
Tororo. He was found with a home-made bomb which he intended to
plant in one of the beer depots in the district.
</P>
<P>
The soldier confessed that he had been having a network in
eastern Uganda, Central and West Nile regions.
</P>
<P>
The minister also revealed that the government troops attacked
and overran an enemy camp in Rwenzori mountains bordering the
Democratic Republic of Congo and captured some documents showing
all the details of the rebels of the Allied Democratic Forces.
</P>
<P>
This information is going to help the security agents track
down these criminals and arrest them.
</P>
<P>
Terrorism is a pretty new thing in Uganda. The minister called
on the press and general public to assist the government in
checking the rampant crime.
</P>
<P>
Since 1997, there have been 28 urban terrorist incidents in
Uganda which have claimed 55 lives and injured 183 others.
Twenty-two of these cases have occurred in the capital city of
Kampala. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
