<HEADLINE> Student Murder in Uganda Not Linked to Terrorism: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The weekend killing of three
students of the renowned Makerere University by an unidentified
gunman has nothing to do with rampant terrorism in Uganda, a
senior security officer said.
</P>
<P>
Henry Tumukhunde, director of military intelligence, told
reporters here Wednesday afternoon that the above case is just a
case of serious murder.
</P>
<P>
As the investigations are still going on, it is too early to
comment on the nature of the murder. There has not been enough
evidence so far indicating that the case is a result of terrorism,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The three students were shot dead by a gunman near a gate of
the university at 10:30 p.m. Friday night. They were reportedly
followed by the assailant in a vehicle from the downtown area.
</P>
<P>
The shoot-out triggered off a large student demonstration
through the center of the capital city the next morning and a big
vigil in the evening.
</P>
<P>
Students blamed this on the laxity of security agencies and
demanded security be strengthened in the fenceless university.
</P>
