<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Urges G8 Ministers to Free Poor Nations from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) said Wednesday that perpetuating the debt
crisis denies the social and economic rights of hundreds of
millions of impoverished children and women, and it urged G8,
seven major Western nations plus Russia, to take real steps to
break the debt bondage of the world's poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
"Children and women have an absolute right to basic education
and health," UNICEF Executive Director Carol Bellamy said,"
Nations freed from excessive debt burdens are prepared to make
these rights a reality and their creditors have a moral obligation
to help them do so."
</P>
<P>
The appeal came before G8 ministers are to meet in Cologne,
Germany, on June 18-20.
</P>
<P>
"On the eve of the new millennium, it is no longer that
hundreds of millions of people be held in debt bondage to the
world's rich countries," Bellamy said, "The G8 ministers could
take the lead in ensuring that countless millions of children and
women are no longer victims of, but, instead, participants in,
today's global economic system."
</P>
<P>
Bellamy said that a growing international movement favors
dramatic debt relief and urged the G8 ministers to make a
significant reforms in the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC)
Initiative.
</P>
<P>
HIPC was launched in 1960 to provide relief to 41 of the
world's poorest nations -- the great majority of which are in
Sub-Saharan Africa -- but has failed to move far and fast enough
to achieve its modest objectives. Few target nations have
benefited and, because HIPC relief is tied to export earnings,
plummeting commodity prices have dealt an unexpected added blow to
the initiative.
</P>
<P>
Bellamy said it is a sad irony that this year's 10th
anniversary of the Convention on the Rights of the Child (CRC)
coincides with the 10th year of a virtual free-fall in economic
development assistance to the world's poorest nations. "That only
makes it more imperative that debt relief be give a human face,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF's appeal coincides with the Day of the Africa Child, and
Bellamy urged G8 ministers to take special heed of how the
external debt crisis has hurt sub-Saharan Africa, which owed 84
billion U.S. dollars in 1980 and now owes more than 225 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Sub-Saharan Africa is caught in a debt trap which which
creates an impossible drain on the region's fragile economies,"
she said. "Child mortality reates in this region are one-third
higher than the average for other developing countries, and
maternal mortality rates are nearly three times greater."
</P>
<P>
"More than a third of the children have not been immunized and
approximately half the population is illiterate," she said. "Yet
the region is forced to spend more on serving its external debt
than on the health and education of its 306 million children," she
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Tobacco Levy to Be Halved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Finance Ministry of Zimbabwe
said Wednesday it will be reducing the controversial 10 percent
tobacco levy by half in the year 2000 budget.
</P>
<P>
At present, farmers pay 10 percent levy on gross sales, of
which five percent is apportioned to the producer and five
percent to the buyer.
</P>
<P>
According to the Zimbabwe Tobacco Association (ZTA), the buyer
discounts the cost of the levy to the seller through the price
offered and thus the farmer effectively pays a 10-percent levy on
all tobacco sales.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Herbert Murerwa Wednesday told delegates at
the 39th annual congress of the ZTA that the government would
undertake to further review the levy, introduced in 1996, to
assist the farmers.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco is Zimbabwe's single largest foreign exchange earner,
netting some 32 percent of total annual earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
