<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Despite Zimbabwean cabinet's
approval of the outstanding five percent increment back-dated to
January, civil servants in Harare and other cities held strike
Wednesday demanding 20 percent cost of living adjustment.
</P>
<P>
The civil servants' decision to down tools came a day after the
cabinet agreed to pay them the additional five percent to the 25
percent increase awarded last December to cushion the workers
against economic hardships.
</P>
<P>
About 140,000 civil servants were expected to participate in
the nationwide strike whose ending would depend on the
government's willingness to start negotiations on a further 20
percent cost of living adjustment.
</P>
<P>
The civil servants gave the government until Friday to resume
negotiations to resolve the issue.
</P>
<P>
