<HEADLINE> Angola Needs $500 Million to Restore Agricultural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A senior Angolan official said here
 Wednesday that the country needs about 500 million U.S. dollars
to restore its agricultural irrigation facilities damaged in the
civil war.
</P>
<P>
Dario Daniel Catata, Deputy Minister of Agriculture and Rural
Development, said "Agriculture is one of the foundations of
Angola's economic development. And the restoration of these
facilities is of great importance to increase agricultural output
and employment."
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the capital needed for the
restoration of agricultural facilities will rely mainly on
international assistance. However, the Angolan government also
has some capital on hand for some priority projects aiming to
develop food products.
</P>
<P>
Angola used to be an agricultural giant, with sufficient food
to feed its people and even for some export. However, the
protracted civil war has severely damaged the country's
agricultural infrastructure, forcing farmers flee from their homes
and farm lands.
</P>
<P>
The southern African country is short of over 500,000 tons of
grain this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
