<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Population of Black Rhinos on Rise in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The number of black rhinos in
Kenya, a species of wild animals on the brink of extinction in
the world, has increased to 470 heads from 280 in 1984, the Kenya
Wildlife Service (KWS) announced here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to KWS, there were over 20,000 black rhinos in Kenya
In the 1970s. However, the number of this precious species
declined drastically due to rampant poaching activities.
</P>
<P>
To strengthen its management of the wildlife games in the
country, the Kenyan government in 1990 set up KWS and worked out
the act of wildlife conservation. It also established an
anti-poaching task force, the first of

its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
Timothy Oloo, an official working with the rhino protection
program in KWS, told Xinhua that each black rhino has its own file
including its serial number, the birth date, the place of birth,
sex and health conditions. Each of them has also been tagged for
easy tracking by the wildlife personnel.
</P>
<P>
The black rhinos are now mainly distributed over six national
wildlife parks and six private pastoral farms. Of which,
three-fourth are in the national parks, Oloo said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Calls to Ratify African Charter on Rights and </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African
Unity (OAU) Wednesday called on member states to sign and ratify
the African Charter on the Rights and Welfare of the Child to
enable it come into force and implement it at their national
levels.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by OAU Assistant Secretary General Pascal
Gayama at a gathering held at Africa Hall here to mark this year's
"the Day of the African Child", which falls on June 16, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Gayama said the charter which was adopted in 1990 still lacks
the required number of ratifications to enable it come into force.
</P>
<P>
He said, "today 12 member states have ratified the African
Charter and only 28 have signed it," adding that "the Charter
needs only 15 ratifications to enable it come into force."
</P>
<P>
On the theme "peace education" of this year's "the Day of the
African Child", Gayama pointed out that peace education is
tolerance, mutual understanding, respect of human rights, love for
each other and democracy.
</P>
<P>
"As the future generation, they (African children) have a role
to play to propagate peace and live in peace," he said, adding
that "a child should therefore know and be taught about peace."
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion, Speaker of Ethiopian Parliament Dawit
Yohannes said peace means harmony, tolerance, wholeness and
well-being in all human relationships.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to "develop the culture of peace", saying
that "in the process of constructing a culture of peace, education
should play a significant role."
</P>
<P>
There was a dialogue on the theme "peace education" between
children, teachers from various schools of Ethiopia and Ethiopian
Government officials, OAU officials and representatives from the
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and the International Committee
of Red Cross (ICRC) at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
June 16 was named by the 26th session of OAU summit in 1990 as
"the Day of African Child" in remembrance of the massacre
perpetrated by then racist regime of South Africa in Soweto in
which many innocent children lost their lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
