<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Prices Remain Unchanged in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua)-- The Labor Department said
Wednesday that consumer prices held steady in May after a big jump
the month before.
</P>
<P>
The falling energy prices balanced rising food costs to help
keep the Consumer Price Index flat last month, the Department
said.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile energy and food categories, the core
prices rose just 0.1 percent as clothing and auto prices declined
and medical and housing costs edged up. April's consumer prices
increased an unexpectedly sharp 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the annual rate of inflation felt by
consumers is 2.6 percent, compared to a 1.6 percent rise for all
of 1998, the smallest in a dozen years.
</P>
<P>
Although the April spike in prices was surprisingly large, many
analysts have predicted more moderate inflation for the rest of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said prices are expected to rise as other countries
begin to recover from nearly two years of global financial
turmoil, and world demand will pick up.
</P>
<P>
Energy prices dropped 1.3 percent in May after a record 6.1
percent jump in April. Gasoline prices fell back 2.7 percent after
a 15 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
Electricity and natural gas prices also declined in May,
although fuel-oil prices continued to edge up slightly.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, food prices increased 0.4 percent in May, building
on a 0.1 percent April rise.
</P>
<P>
However, clothing prices fell 0.2 percent in May, with the cost
of footwear down 1.3 percent. Computer prices also dropped, by 1.9
percent. The apparel and computer industries continue to be
affected by stiff competition from low-priced imports.
</P>
<P>
The price of new cars and trucks also fell in May, by 0.1
percent, and public transportation costs dropped 1.5 percent.
Airline fares fell 2.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Imports Surge in First Five Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- China's imports surged 15.3
percent in the first five months of the year, the highest growth
rate since May 1996, latest statistics released by the General
Administration of Customs show.
</P>
<P>
The overall trade volume recorded between January and May this
year reached 128.03 billion US dollars, up 3.4 percent from the
same period last year. The increase was largely attributed to the
increase of imports, which hit 60.48 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
China's exports during the period dropped 5.3 percent to 67.55
billion US dollars, but the exports in May reported the first
positive growth rate of 4.2 percent in five months.
</P>
<P>
Among the increased imports, industrial goods accounted for a
major share at 18.7 percent. The importing of chemical goods and
related products grew 30.8 percent; the imports of steel surged 38.
5 percent; paper and paper boards increased by 18.7 percent while
those of electronic products and machinery grew 27.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the import value of primary goods dropped 0.2 percent.
But analysts here say that the decline does not imply a shrinking
in the amount of imports because the price of many primary goods
declined on the world market.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, the volume of a number of primary goods imports
actually increased as did that for cooking oil, sugar, timber and
processed timber and commodity oil.
</P>
<P>
Economic experts have pointed out that the increase of imports
was mainly because of an enlarged domestic demand since late last
year and price cuts among primary goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
