<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Troops Launch Fresh Offensives In Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Indian troops launched fresh
attacks Wednesday in Drass and Batalik areas of Kashmir along with
air raids upon what officials here described as "infiltrated
positions" northeast of Kargil.
</P>
<P>
An army spokesman said at a press briefing here today that
reliable intelligence reports indicated that positions held by the
"sneakers" in certain areas were becoming increasingly untenable
for them due to high rate of attrition and lack of ration,
ammunition and medical cover.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) reported that "heavy
concentration" of Pakistani troops along the so-called line of
control in the Neelam Valley area of Pakistan side. The report
could not be confirmed here.
</P>
<P>
Asked how long the military operations would take to complete,
the army spokesman said the "intruders" had been pushed from
positions inside Indian territory to three to 3.5 km, adding "you
can not expect results overnight".
</P>
<P>
With the fierce fighting going on in Kashmir, Indian officials
claimed that U.S. President Bill Clinton had expressed his support
to New Delhi's stand on the on-going conflict with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Clinton held a 20-minute talk with Pakistan Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif through telephone Tuesday following his call to and a
10-minute conversation with Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari
Vajpayee a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
In his talk with Sharif, according to a White House spokesman,
"the president basically indicated that he did not see how
progress could be made on this issue (the conflict in Kashmir)
until those forces are withdrawn".
</P>
<P>
India has seen this as a major diplomatic boost for it,
asserting that its position on the current conflict had been
recognized by the United States and Clinton was in fact asking
Pakistan to pull back its forces from where Indian claimed as its
territory.
</P>
<P>
"We are glad to see that the basic fact of the situation and
the whole misadventure, originating in Pakistan, has been
recognized by the U.S. government," a senior government official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Indian officials, Including Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee
and Defense Minister George Fernandes, vowed to continue the
military operations till the last "intruder" from Pakistan was
thrown out.
</P>
<P>
They have made it clear that there would be no talks with
Pakistan before the pullout of Pakistan troops and "mercenaries".
</P>
<P>
However, the External Affairs Ministry spokesman said that
India had never been adverse to a dialogue with Pakistan based on
the Lahore Declaration signed between the prime ministers of the
two neighbors last February and the Simla Agreement in 1972.
</P>
<P>
Government officials declared that India was not in the least
interested in seeing a military flare-up, saying New Delhi's
policy was aimed at building "a stable, long-term, cooperative
relationship" with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking at everything pragmatically keeping in view the
mutuality of interests" and other factors, a high-ranking official
said, adding there were powerful interests in the business
communities of both countries to speedily normalize bilateral
ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
