<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Helps Arrest Environmental Degradation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank announced on
Wednesday that it has approved 135 million U.S. dollars to help
arrest environmental decline, boost agricultural growth, and
ensure better management of scarce land and water resources in the
Shivalik Hills which is one of India's most environmental degraded
areas.
</P>
<P>
The Integrated Watershed Development (Hills II) project builds
on the success of the 1990 First Project of Watershed Development
(Hills I) in the Shivalik Areas which addressed the need for new
technologies and mechanisms for increasing agricultural
production, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
"The project (Hills II) focuses on the most degraded watersheds
in the rain-fed areas, which are primarily dependent on rain for
agricultural production, and targets some of the poorest
populations in India," said Hamdy Eisa, task leader and principal
agriculturist for the South Asia Rural Development sector.
</P>
<P>
"In particular, the project will reach the most vulnerable
groups, especially women and landless labor. This will contribute
significantly to poverty alleviation in the project states," Eisa
said.
</P>
<P>
The total project cost is estimated at 193 million dollars, of
which the bank will finance 85 million dollars and the
International Development Association (IDA), the bank's
concessionary lending arm, will finance 50 million dollars. The
governments of the five participating states and beneficiaries
will jointly contribute an equivalent of 58 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The IDA credit is on standard terms, with a maturity of 35
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
