<HEADLINE> French Troops Jump to Northern Kosovo Ahead of Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- French troops joining the U.N.
peacekeeping force in Kosovo (KFOR) rushed to a village north of
Kosovo's capital Pristina Wednesday afternoon to prevent fighting
between Serbs and Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted a spokesman of the French
troops as saying that 300 French soldiers rushed to the village of
Vucitrn in armored vehicles while 600 others flew in by helicopters
late Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The move was demanded by the Yugoslav military liaison office,
who said that Yugoslav forces pulling out of Kosovo are coming under
more and more threats from the local Albanians.
</P>
<P>
The abrupt movement of the French soldiers, which was made two
days ahead of schedule, went on without any accident with the
Albanian guerrilla group the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA), said the
spokesman Lieutenant-Colonel Philippe Tanguy.
</P>
<P>
When the French soldiers arrived in Vucitrn, which is 30
kilometers north of Pristina, gunshots were heard in the mountains
nearby, said AFP..
</P>
<P>
Figting reportedly broke out Wednesday afternoon near Vucitrn
between withdrawing Yugoslav forces and the KLA.  
</P>
