<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- NATO and the Kosovo Liberation Army
have reached agreement on an outline plan for disarming KLA
fighters, according to British government sources.
</P>
<P>
They said on Wednesday that the framework agreement was reached
at talks between military officials in Tirana and had been
forwarded to the North Atlantic Council, NATO's ruling political
body. Details were still being discussed, a Reuters report said.
</P>
<P>
"Discussions are still going on on the modalities of
demilitarization," one government source was quoted saying.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, a KLA representative in London said ethnic
Albanian guerrillas would not disarm in northern Kosovo until
Russia agreed to place its troops under a unified command with
NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
But British officials said Russia's peacekeeping role in Kosovo
had not been included in the Tirana talks. They said the framework
agreement included a timetable for KLA disarmament and NATO
intended to hold the KLA leadership to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
"It was never imagined that the KLA would disarm overnight,"
one official said. 
