<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Calls for Peaceful Ballot in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Security Council on
Wednesday called on all parties to take the necessary steps to
allow the ballot for East Timor's future to go peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Following consultations, the council issued a press statement
by June president, Gambia's Baboucarr-Blaise Ismaila Jagne, saying
that it would like to see the electoral process to be in "an
atmosphere free of intimidation and violence from all quarters".
</P>
<P>
East Timor is set for a direct ballot on August 8 to determine
whether the majority of the people in the non-self-governing
territory, as it is called by the U.N. General Assembly, would
choose special autonomy or independence.
</P>
<P>
The voting was agreed to by Indonesia and Portugal on May 5
after long-time talks mediated by the United Nations, which is
charged with organizing and conducting the voting process.
</P>
<P>
East Timor with an area of 19,000 square kilometers and a
population of 800,000, has been a Portuguese colony until 1975
when Indonesia occupation it following an internal rift.
</P>
<P>
Jakarta annexed it in 1976 and since then the U.N. has been
trying to find a solution to the dispute.
</P>
<P>
During consultations, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's
personal representative Jamsheed Marker on East Timor briefed the
15 council members on the current situation there.
</P>
<P>
Members expressed their full support for the work of the U.N.
Mission in East Timor which comprises some 900 international
staff, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
The Mission's chief electoral officer Jeffrey Fischer has
already arrived in Dili, capital of East Timor, a U.N. spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Currently the U.N. has 127 international staff on the ground and
the first group of 42 civilian police are due to arrive in Dili
this Saturday.
</P>
<P>
They are from Australia, Ireland, New Zealand, Spain, Britain
and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Annan has appointed Alan James Mills of Australia as
the Mission's civilian police commissioner. He has begun his work
in Dili already.
</P>
<P>
Council members were pleased with the good cooperation so far
by all the parties and appreciate the measures taken by Indonesia
to ensure a stable security situation for the ballot.
</P>
<P>
They "noted that the responsibility for creating a secure
environment for the process "lies with the Government of
Indonesia", the statement said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
