<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Points to Tobacco Damage to Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The World Health
Organization (WTO) on Wednesday issued a new report on how tobacco
smoke damages children's health.
</P>
<P>
Adverse effects of environmental tobacco smoke include
pneumonia, bronchitis, coughing, wheezing, worsening of asthma and
middle-ear infections, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Children exposure to tobacco smoke may also contribute to
cardiovascular disease in adulthood, it added.
</P>
<P>
WHO said some 700 million of the world's children, or almost
half of all children worldwide live in the home of a smoker.
</P>
</TEXT>
