<HEADLINE>   Philippine Archers Appeal for Private Financial Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Financial shortage pinches the
Filipino archers' preparation for the 40th World Archery
Championships (WAC) in Riom, France slated on July 16-30.
</P>
<P>
With the Philippine Sports Commission's denial of financial
assistance, the National Archery Association of the Philippines (
NAAP) is in quandary in looking for funds to support the archers'
participation for the WAC, a qualifying tournament for the 2000
Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to raise more funds, the NAAP is appealing to the
private sector to lend their helping hands to the archers whose
dream is to compete in the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
"We are asking the private sectors to help our archers and
coaches who have prepared and trained intensively for this event
in the hope that they will be able to participate in the Sydney
Olympics," NAAP President Ramon Lim said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The NAAP strongly believes that the country's archery team has
a better chance to qualify because the top 43 in the WAC final
standing will qualify for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
As gold medalists in the Chang-Mai and Jakarta Southeast Asia
Games and other archery events since 1955, the NAAP is confident
that the Filipino archers can compete against the world's best
bow and arrow specialists.
</P>
<P>
The NAAP said aside from the World Championship, the
Philippines' archery team is also set to compete in the Asian
Championship to be held in Beijing, China in August.
</P>
<P>
Among the male archers that achieved outstanding performances
in the local and international scenes were Francisco Naranilla Jr.,
Miguel Martinez, Manuel Lopez, Victoriano Tabora and Teofisto
Nugud while the top female archers that brought home pride and
glory were Jocelyn Guerrero and Joan Chan Tabanag. 
</P>
</TEXT>
