<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, U.S. Differ Over Lifting of Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- France and the United States still
differ over the lifting of the U.N.-imposed economic sanctions on
Iraq, said visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton and his French
counterpart, Jacques Chirac, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference with Chirac at the Elysee
presidential palace, Clinton said that Washington wants to
maintain the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in Iraq as a strict
control preventing the development of arms of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
"Without a strict control mechanism, Saddam Hussein will try to
rebuild his arsenal of mass destruction," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also warned that if an international strict control on
the flow of arms of mass destruction is not imposed, the world
could be confronted with a "proliferation of weapons of high
technology" within 10 years.
</P>
<P>
In that case, such arms will fall into the hands of terrorists
and members of organized crimes, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said that France wants the U.N. to replace the
commission with a new U.N. mechanism of arms control in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the U.N. should re-examine its economic
sanctions imposed on Iraq since 1990 after Iraq invaded Kuwait, he
said, because it is the Iraqi people who have suffered most from
the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The French president said that France does not agree with a
British-Dutch proposal on suspending oil embargo on Iraq as the
first step to alleviate economic sanctions, a plan which is
supported by the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
