<HEADLINE> Lobang Toinzhub Meets Brazilian Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Lobang Toinzhub, vice-chairman of
Tibet Autonomous Region, and a Brazilian delegation met today and
exchanged views on human rights.
</P>
<P>
The visitors are here for a four-day visit at the invitation of
the Chinese Government.
</P>
<P>
Lobang Toinzhub briefed the visitors headed by Brazilian State
Secretary of Human Rights Jose Gregori on Tibet's dramatic changes
since the democratic reform in 1959.
</P>
<P>
Democratic reform outlawed the serf system and gave Tibetan
people the right to live and to develop. Tibetans account for an
overwhelming percentage of delegates to the local people's
congress and government officials in the autonomous region,
according to the vice-chairman.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan working people were classified as serfs prior to
democratic reform, he said. They were, in fact, enslaved by monks,
aristocrats and officials who owned ninety-five percent of the
local wealth and resources while constituting a mere five percent
of the population, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed the delegation on monumental changes in the
region's economy, culture, education and social development.
</P>
<P>
Members of the delegation expressed belief that Tibet will
continue to advance in spite of difficulties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urged to "Untie the Knot", People's Daily Commentary (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The People's Daily, China's
leading newspaper, is to publish tomorrow a commentary entitled "
It Is up to the One Who Tied the Knot to Untie It," in the wake of
Thomas Pickering's China visit, in which the U.S. President's
personal envoy attempted to explain the U.S.-led NATO attack on
China's embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
The commentary says the U.S.-led NATO wantonly attacked the
Chinese embassy in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia on May 8, a
move that "brutally violated China's sovereignty and dignity and
caused heavy casualties and severe property losses." "The Chinese
government has taken a firm stance against the act," it says.
</P>
<P>
On June 16, U.S. President's Personal Envoy and Undersecretary
of State Thomas Pickering arrived in Beijing to present to the
Chinese government a U.S. government report on the results of its
investigation into the attack.
</P>
<P>
Even though the atrocity took place almost 40 days ago, the U.S.
explanation still "played the old tune," the commentary says.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.S. explanation, what led to the "tragic
mistaken bombing" were three reasons: the use of techniques used
in the field by the Army that led to a wrong target location; the
tardily updated databases; and the target review process which
failed to detect and correct the afore-said two mistakes.
</P>
<P>
"The explanation still lacks any convincing factual basis or
rational logic so it is still not justified and its conclusion of
'mistaken bombing' is not convincing," the commentary says, adding
that "It naturally cannot be accepted by the Chinese government
and people."
</P>
</TEXT>
