<HEADLINE> Indian Claims to Regain Strategic Height in Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- India said Thursday that its
troops had regained a strategic height in Batalik, north Kashmir,
after a fierce battle which began Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) reported from Srinagar, capital
of the India-controlled Kashmir, that "5031" height was captured
after inflicting heavy casualty on what India termed as
"intruders" from Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
PTI said that heavy fightings were continued in several spots
of Kargil sector with support of the Indian Air Force, which
launched its strikes on Pakistan positions in the disputed area on
May 26.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Indian media reported today that the Pakistan Army
were believed to have started withdrawing from pockets that had
been encircled by the Indian forces while despatching
reinforcements to back their stronger positions in the Kargil
sector.
</P>
<P>
PTI quoted official sources as claiming that there was a heavy
military buildup in Pakistan side along the so-called line of
control in Skardu sector of Pakistan controlled Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
With no sign of diplomatic breakthrough, the two neighbors have
ordered their troops along the border in high alert.
</P>
<P>
Chief of Indian Naval Staff Sushil Kumar asserted today in
Mumbai that the Indian Navy was in "maximum combat readiness" for
retaliation or counter strike in the event of any "adventurism" by
Pakistan including a nuclear strike at sea.
</P>
<P>
"We have put together maximum combat capability in the western
theater by additionally deploying ships from the Eastern Fleet,"
Kumar said.
</P>
<P>
According to PTI, Kumar said at his first press conference
after taking over as the navy chief that Pakistan Navy Fleet was
on a red alert and was preparing for action.
</P>
<P>
India and Pakistan failed to reach any agreement on defusing,
to say nothing of cease-fire, the on-going conflict in Kashmir in
talks between foreign ministers of the two countries last week.
</P>
<P>
New Delhi maintained that it was Pakistan which was responsible
for the conflict and therefore, as a precondition for further
talks, Islamabad should take the right steps to fully restore the
status quo ante along the line of control.
</P>
<P>
Government officials her declared that India was not in the
least interested in seeing a military flare-up, saying New Delhi's
policy was aimed at building "a stable, long-term, cooperative
relationship" with Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
