<HEADLINE> Canadian Murderer Faces Lethal Injection Again in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian murderer will die
Thursday by lethal injection in Taxas, U.S., barring last minute
intervention by the U.S. Supreme Court or by Governor of Texas
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
If put to death, Joseph Stanley Faulder will be the first known
Canadian executed in the U.S. since 1952, the "National Post" of
Canada reported.
</P>
<P>
Faulder, 61-year-old former auto mechanic, has been twice
convicted in the 1975 stabbing murder of Inez Phillips, a 75-year-
old widow in the east Texas town of Gladewater.
</P>
<P>
Faulder's request for clemency has been rejected by the Texas
Board of Pardons and Parole in a 18-0 vote and he is resigned to
his fate again in six months.
</P>
<P>
On December 10, he was within 30 minutes of being injected with
a lethal mix of sodium thiopental, pancuronium bromide and
potassium chloride when the Supreme Court issued a temporary stay.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy wrote to U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright Wednesday, asking her to use
influence for more time to examine claims that Texas violated
Faulder's human rights when he was arrested in 1977. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
