<HEADLINE> U.S. Urged to "Untie the Knot", People's Daily Commentary (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On the incorrect targeting location method, the U.S. claimed
that all other targets were located by making use of precision
targeting for air attacks. "Why was it that this airstrike
breached the operational rules and unusually used a targeting
system normally operated in the field by the army for a target
that the U.S. military considered so important?" the People's
Daily asks.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. side cannot deny that they knew the precise location
of the Chinese embassy in Yugoslavia. People, henceforth, can
hardly believe that the U.S. military used an outdated map in
which the Chinese embassy was unidentified," it says.
</P>
<P>
On the explanation that the U.S. labeled the target as the
Yugoslav Federal Directorate for Supply and Procurement (FDSP),
the commentary describes it as "rhetoric to fool people," for the
two buildings are not only far from each other but also bear no
resemblance in physical structure.
</P>
<P>
The commentary considered the database flaw as "a tale from The
Arabian Nights." "The situation demonstrated that the U.S. side
fully knew the overall layout of foreign missions in Belgrade," it
says.
</P>
<P>
It is known to all that the United States had been planning the
strikes against Yugoslavia for a long time, the commentary says.
Long before the military actions against Yugoslavia, it had been
photographing, mapping and surveying all parts of Yugoslavia,
Belgrade in particular, by various high-tech means. In the many
rounds of attacks against Yugoslav targets in central Belgrade,
the U.S. side had avoided bombing foreign embassies in Yugoslavia
only dozens or several hundreds of meters away from the targets. "
How should such precision be explained in the light of the savage
attack on the Chinese Embassy," the commentary asks.
</P>
