<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan CPPCC Members Hail Democratic Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Tibetan members of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), the country's
leading advisory body, today hailed the 40th anniversary of
democratic reforms in Tibet carried out since the Dalai Lama
clique's failed rebellion in 1959.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 CPPCC members attended today's forum to share their
views on monumental changes which have taken place in Tibet over
the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
CPPCC members denounced the feudalistic religious and political
regime in place before the democratic reform. They noted that the
former local government, aristocrats and upper-class lamas
oppressed serfs by denying them any freedom, access to means of
production. Serfs were also denied the right to elect
representatives or stand for office and their right to education.
</P>
<P>
They also pointed out that the democratic reform opened a new
era in Tibet and completely dismantled the old system. The
democratic reform also led to freedom for serfs and slaves who
made up 95 percent of the region's population before 1959.
</P>
<P>
The CPPCC members praised development over the past four
decades, especially the monumental development in recent years.
Official statistics show that Tibet's gross domestic product (GDP)
has surpassed the national average for five years running. Living
standards for local residents have also improved rapidly.
</P>
<P>
They quoted President Jiang Zemin as saying: "Tibet has
developed and prospered due to democratic reforms, as well as the
region's adherence to the socialist road and persistence in
carrying out reforms and opening." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
