<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Police Seize Counterfeit Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Law enforcement departments in the
Chinese capital had seized 10.55 million yuan in counterfeit
currency between January 1998 and April this year.
</P>
<P>
The departments arrested 404 suspects involved in 221
counterfeiting and trafficking cases, according to a police
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said that most of the fake money was smuggled into China
from overseas and noted that the counterfeit bills are difficult
to detect.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that Beijing has witnessed an increasing number
of counterfeiting and trafficking cases in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Law enforcement departments handled an average of less than 100
counterfeiting cases annually between 1994-1997. However, the 151
cases in 1998 involved counterfeit currency with a face value of 6.
75 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
He said Beijing police cracked 70 cases and seized 3.8 million
yuan in fake money in the first four months of this year alone.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that over 80 percent of suspects caught in
counterfeiting and trafficking cases over the past five years have
been non-Beijing residents.
</P>
<P>
The number of cases involving small denomination five and 10
yuan notes has been on the rise in recent years, according to the
spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
