<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Deficit Remains at Record High in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Commerce Department said
Thursday that the trade deficit in April was 18.9 billion dollars,
matching a revised estimate of the deficit in March and holding
steady at a record high.
</P>
<P>
Since global financial turmoil continued to hamper U.S. trade
performance, the trade deficit is running at an annual rate of
218.1 billion dollars, compared to the all-time high of 169.3
billion dollars set last year.
</P>
<P>
However, because other countries began a tentative recovery
from recession this spring, U.S. exports have started to pick up
again.
</P>
<P>
U.S. exports, which had fallen for five previous months staged
a small comeback in April. Exports rose 1.2 percent to 78 billion
dollars, including all categories from food to toys to cars.
</P>
<P>
U.S. imports have also continued to rise, climbing 1 percent to
97 billion dollars in April, a record high. Imports of foods,
feeds and beverages reached a record 3.5 billion dollars and
imports of consumer and industrial goods were also up. But imports
of motor vehicles and parts declined in April by 5.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Imports from Japan declined, pulling the sensitive deficit with
Japan down 13.1 percent to 5.6 billion U.S. dollars, the first
drop since November.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit with Mexico, a partner in the North American
Free Trade Agreement, also declined in April by 32.5 percent to
1.7 billion due to a sharp drop in imports.
</P>
<P>
However, the April deficit with OPEC countries was more than
doubled in April to 1.8 billion U.S. dollars, the most since
October 1997. That was largely due to a sharp spike in oil and gas
prices because of the production limits.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. deficit with the 15-nation European Union
increased by 9.7 percent to 2.9 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration argues that the overall trade
deficit has a positive side: As the only major economy doing well,
the United States is playing a valuable role providing markets for
other countries struggling to get back on their feet.
</P>
<P>
Some economists also note that cheap imports have helped keep
inflation low here during a period of unusually high employment
and heavy consumers spending. But government officials are worried
that too big a trade deficit could cause U.S. industries to go
further to pressure Congress for protectionist measures.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report Thursday, the Commerce Department said steel
imports fell by 8.6 percent in April, less than the 14 percent the
government had first estimated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
