<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Simple Machine Brings Opportunities for Sustainable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A simple low-cost machine
based on a diesel motor is changing the patterns of life and
enabling thousands of rural people across Mali to increase their
productivity and income generation, the United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) officials said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The machine, known as the "Multi-dimensional Platform," can be
used for crushing, grinding, shredding, sawing, drilling, welding,
pumping water or generating electricity.
</P>
<P>
A UNDP-supported project has helped 45 villages to finance and
install the platforms. The target is to cover 500 villagers in
five years.
</P>
<P>
Each village is first asked to appoint a small group of women
to operate and manage the platforms and to mobilize counterpart
funds. The women appointed are trained on the functioning of the
platform, including how to operate it and sell its services.
</P>
<P>
Seventy percent of women in Mali are illiterate, UNDP officials
said. The women's group that manages the platform often includes
illiterates, and the new role gives them a strong incentive to
acquire basis literacy and arithmetic skills, for which help is
given.
</P>
<P>
In a country like Mali, where electricity is still a distant
reality for most rural communities, the impact of the machine on
daily life has been dramatic. By switching from human and animal
energy sources to the multi-dimensional platform, rural Malians,
particularly the women, have seen a significant reduction in their
workload.
</P>
<P>
This, in turn, has allowed them to devote more time to other
income-generating activities such as market gardening and
trading.
</P>
<P>
Installation and maintenance of the platform is by local
artisans who are given any needed additional training by the
project. The maintenance is a direct business relationship between
the women managers and local artisans.
</P>
<P>
Cereal processing has been the main revenue-generating activity
for which the platform is used. It is also popular in powering
water pumps which has led to significant reduction of the workload
of rural Malians who no longer have to spend hours searching for
water for domestic use.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, by making electricity available, the platform has
had strong social impact on village life, making possible such
activity as evening classes for those unable to attend regular
classes, refrigeration and use of television. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
