<HEADLINE> Asia Set for New Undersea Fiber Optic Cable Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Ten telecommunications companies
from seven countries in the Asia-Pacific Region signed a
memorandum on Wednesday in Kunming, capital of southwest China's
Yunnan Province, calling for the development of Asia's longest
undersea fiber optic cable network.
</P>
<P>
The network will be developed at a cost of between 700-800
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The 22-km No.2 Asia-Pacific fiber optic cable will run from the
cities of Kitaibaraki and Chikura in Japan to Kuantan of Malaysia
and Singapore, via Shanghai, Shantou, Hong Kong, and Toucheng in
Taiwan. The project is scheduled for completion in 2002 and the
network will become Asia's leading undersea fiber optic cable
network in terms of its handling capacity and the use of advanced
technology.
</P>
<P>
The line will be connected to one transpacific undersea fiber
optic line linking China and the U.S. and another line linking
Japan and the United States. The new cable is expected to promote
telecommunications development in the Asia-Pacific Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
