<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Dissociates from ILO Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has announced dissociation
of itself from a current resolution adopted at the 87th session of
the International Labor Conference (ILC) in Geneva which accused
the country of widespread use of forced labor and restriction of
freedom of association.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release of the Myanmar Foreign Ministry
Thursday night, Myanmar will cease participation in activities
connected with Convention 29 (Forced Labor Convention) and
Convention 87 (Convention on the Freedom of Association).
</P>
<P>
A number of western nations pushed through the resolution at
the current session of the ILC. The Myanmar government says the
resolution is an unfair and biased one.
</P>
<P>
"This is an action which is unprecedented and is also not in
conformity with the existing procedures of the International Labor
Organization (ILO)," the press release said.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the unfairness of the exercise, its lack of balance
and objectivity as well as the underlying political motives,
Myanmar finds it impossible to accept such deplorable and
unscrupulous action on the part of those nations who want to
interfere and meddle in the internal affairs of Myanmar," it
stated.
</P>
<P>
The participation will cease "until such time that Myanmar
receives fair and equitable treatment that must necessarily be
accorded to all members of the ILO," it warned, adding that the
country will continue to comply with the conventions to which it
is a party.
</P>
<P>
A Commission of Inquiry on Forced Labor in Myanmar was formed
in 1997 which the Myanmar government then objected, saying that
there existed no ground for the establishment.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar government also refuted the report of the
commission and its recommendations issued in July 1998, saying
that they are one-sided, biased and based on unfounded allegations
made by dissidents.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar became a member of the ILO in 1948, a few months after
it regained independence from the British colonial rule, and had
ratified 19 ILO conventions.
</P>
<P>
The country also charged some western nations with attempting
to use the ILO to further their political aims in Myanmar since
the early 1990s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Special Saudi market bonds valued at 1.3 billion
U.S. dollars are expected to be issued soon.
</P>
<P>
Local press reported Thursday that two banks expect Saudi
Arabia to issue more special bonds to cover payments to
contractors and suppliers.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia had issued special bonds to cover contractors'
dues when it faced shortage in liquidity.
</P>
<P>
Though the date of issuing has not been fixed, market sources
expect it this month.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Iran is considering participation in several joint
ventures in Egypt in the fields of industry, services, transport
and infrastructure with investments of some 200 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Hakim Haggag, president of the Egypt-Iran Weaving and
Spinning Company in Suez said that an Iranian economic and
industrial delegation is expected in Cairo in the first week of
July to discuss the prospects of Iranian investments in productive
development projects in the free zone, north of the Suez Gulf, and
the possibility of establishing a huge complex for weaving and
textile.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian side will put up 300 million Egyptian pounds (88
million dollars) for the complex and Iran will invest 100 million
pounds (29.4 million dollars), the Arabic Alam Al Yom reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Haggag, who is also chairman of the Holding Company for
Weaving, Spinning and Textiles, added that the Iranian side was
also considering expansion of the Egypt-Iran company by investing
some 15 million pounds (4.4 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The expansion, among other projects, includes the establishment
of a factory for non-textile products at a total cost of 10
million pounds (2.9 million dollars) and a project for dying yarn
at approximately half a million pounds (140,000 dollars).
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Total direct Arab investments in Arab countries
reached 2.25 billion dollars in 1998, up about 42.1 percent from
the total 1.59 billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to figures quoted by the official WAM news agency
Thursday, the United Arab Emirates (UAE) invested 325 million
dollars in licensed projects in Arab countries, which represented
14.4 percent of total inter-Arab investments.
</P>
<P>
The UAE ranked third after Lebanon and Egypt, which put up 400
million dollars and 385 million dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- British Gas company has won the tender for oil and
gas exploration in Israel's territorial waters along the
Mediterranean coast, local daily The Jerusalem Post reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the tender was issued by Israeli National
Infrastructure Ministry.
</P>
<P>
British Gas's activities here will bring an end to the boycott
of Israeli oil exploration by the world's leading companies.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's Rada Electronic Industries Company has
signed a deal with the American Boeing company to supply it with a
package of automatic testing systems for its 777 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post said Thursday that the deal also includes
maintenance services and full technical support.
</P>
<P>
It marks the first time that Rada has sold a testing service
package and not the testing equipment itself, company officials
were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Bank Hapoalim, Israel's largest bank, is weighing
expanding its investment activities abroad, local daily Haaretz
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the bank may establish a dealing room in
New York or London to deal its investment in the foreign markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
