<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Commit to Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) and the African Economic
Community (AEC) Thursday urged African countries to demonstrate
more seriousness and commitment to the AEC programs that they have
entered into.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Antonio, acting secretary general of the OAU, said here
in his statement at the opening ceremony of the two-day third
ordinary session of OAU/AEC Economic and Social Commission that
"continent integration through the establishment of the AEC is
indeed a major program that should be accorded high priority at
all levels -- national, regional and continental."
</P>
<P>
The Abuja Treaty establishing the AEC came into force in May
1994 and since the signing of the treaty, 43 African countries
have signed and ratified it.
</P>
<P>
Antonio said the first five-year stage of strengthening of the
regional communities has been completed and has now entered the
second stage of the implementation of the AEC which will focus on
trade liberalization and harmonization of customs and sectoral
policies.
</P>
<P>
Referring to international negotiations faced by Africa,
Antonio said "Africa has to be fully prepared for these major
global encounters."
</P>
<P>
The ACP-European Union negotiations for a successor cooperation
 agreement to Lome IV were launched in September 1998 and the
negotiations have been going on in Brussels and elsewhere since
March this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The World Trade Organization is seriously preparing for its 3rd
 ministerial conference in Seattle, the United States, and there
are growing indications of the launching of a new round of
multilateral trade negotiations at this meeting, scheduled for
November 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, Lalla ben barka, deputy
executive secretary of the United Nations Economic Commission for
Africa (ECA), said the establishment of the AEC laid a solid
foundation for economic cooperation and integration among member
states.
</P>
<P>
She hoped African countries and developing countries in general
to present their common position in Lome agreement negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The two-day ministerial meeting followed a two-day preparatory
meeting attended by experts. The second ordinary session was held
in Cairo, Egypt last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
