<HEADLINE> ECA to Hold Regional Hearing on UN's Role in New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Economic
Commission for Africa (ECA) announced Thursday that
representatives of African member states are to meet here from
June 24 to 25 to elaborate proposals on the United Nations in the
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
According to an ECA press release issued here, the two-day
meeting, under the theme "United Nations in the 21st century",
will also draw representatives from the academia, the private
sector, the media, and non- governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is the second in a series of regional hearings
being organized by the five UN regional commissions as part of the
consultative process being undertaken in preparation for the
Millennium Assembly, planned for the year 2000 in New York.
</P>
<P>
"The arrival of the new millennium offers opportunities to
think innovatively on how to address the profound economic, social
and political development challenges facing the world," said the
release.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations as the global organization has the
overriding obligation to consider how to respond to the needs and
aspirations of the great majority of society, still on the margins
of development. The United Nations must rise to the challenge as a
means of restoring faith in the organization's ability to meet the
needs of the 21st century," it said.
</P>
<P>
The African regional hearing will address the five core
priority areas of peace and security, economic and social affairs,
development cooperation, humanitarian affairs and human rights.
</P>
<P>
"Views from the hearings will contribute toward a report to be
prepared by UN Secretary General Kofi Annan outlining a vision for
the UN in the next millennium," it said, adding "these proposals
will be presented to the Millennium Assembly which is expected to
feature a large number of heads of states and government from
member states." 
</P>
</TEXT>
