<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia-U.S. Talks Make Headway n Kosovo Peacekeeping: Ivanov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Russia and the United States have
made progress in solving their differences over the command of
Kosovo peacekeeping forces, but they are still wide apart over a
separate sector for Russia's peacekeepers, Russian Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a meeting with Finnish Foreign Minister Tarja Ha
lonen, Ivanov told reporters that Russia and the United States
have reached consensus on the use of the Pristina military airport
and the division of tasks for Russian and other countries'
peacekeeping forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Pristina military airport is now under the control of a
contingent of Russian advance troops,which entered Kosovo
unexpectedly last weekend ahead of NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said that the two sides also agreed on the participation
of Russia's troops in the command structure of the Kosovo
Peacekeeping Force(KFOR). But he added that the two sides will
continue discussing the possibility of giving Russia a separate
sector in the war-battered Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
Russia only hopes to take part in the peacekeeping mission in
Kosovo on an equal basis with other countries , he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the top Russian diplomat said that it is possible for
Russia to make compromise in its negotiations with Washington, but
the compromise should not undermine Russia's interests.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov reiterated the necessity of disarming the Kosovo
Liberation Army (KLA), saying that KLA' s disarmament is "
absolutely necessary" in settling the Kosovo crisis and a task of
the KFOR.
</P>
<P>
Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev and U.S.Defense
Secretary William Cohen entered into the second day of
negotiations Thursday in the Finnish capital on Russia's
peacekeeping role in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
They will be joined later by Ivanov and U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, who arrived here Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Before meeting Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, Albright
said the United States has made clear that there would be no
separate sector for Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
