<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, U.S. Agree on Western Strategy in Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton
and French President Jacques Chirac reached wide agreement
Thursday on the Western strategy in the Balkans, including
economic aid and a future stabilization plan for the southeast
European region.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference after concluding their talks at the
Elysee presidential palace, Clinton and Chirac said that the
priorities now are to let the Kosovo refugees return home in
security, and to arrange a Western-sponsored "Pact of Stability"
for the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
They said that the West should help the Balkan countries
maintain peace and seek economic development through an aid
program. But they did not mention any specific plan.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Europe differ widely over who should pay for the
reconstruction of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has asked the European Union to provide "a lion's
share" of an economic aid package for Kosovo, because the U.S.
has paid most of the costs of the NATO operation against
Yugoslavia. This argument has been rejected by France.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Chirac also agreed that Western countries will not
send any aid, except humanitarian, to Yugoslavia unless the
country "adopts the rule of democracy."
</P>
<P>
Clinton ruled out the possibility that NATO send commando
troops to Belgrade to arrest Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
and other Serb leaders, who are indicted by the U.N. war crimes
tribunal for "crimes against humanity."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that as long as Milosevic remains inside Serbia,
he is safe from any intervention of foreign troops.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president also said that France has accepted "two or
three" U.S. options on the way to let Russian troops participate
in the Kosovo peacekeeping force (KFOR).
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials holding talks with Russian officials in Helsinki
have suggested that Russian deploy troops in the northern part of
Kosovo, most likely the French-controlled zone, where there is the
largest concentration of Serbs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
