<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Senate Requires Details Before Debating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Two weeks after receiving the list
of ministerial nominees, Nigeria's Senate, or upper chamber of
its legislature, formally opened debate on the proposed cabinet
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, about one hour after the start of the debate, the
Senate requested for further details including especially the
curriculum vitae of the nominees before full debate can resume,
according to the Guardian newspaper Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The request is to be forwarded immediately to President
Olusegun Obasanjo, who returned Wednesday night from his
congratulation tour in S. Africa, by Senate President Evan
Enwerem.
</P>
<P>
Besides, party leaders Abdullah Wali (Sokoto South) for Peoples
 Democratic Party (PDP); Usman Albishir (Yobe North) for All
Peoples Party (APP) and Mojisoluwa Akinfenwa for Alliance for
Democracy (AD) were asked to present desired conditions for
successful nominees.
</P>
<P>
The presentations will be given to another committee of the
whole Senate session Thursday morning after consultations with
their partisans.
</P>
<P>
Conditions to be outlined by the various groups will be
harmonized Thursday and added to already identified criteria for
onward submission to the Presidency.
</P>
<P>
Guidelines listed Wednesday included needs for security
clearance, due tax clearance, record of service, and evidence of
assets declarations. Those who have served in government before
are expected to forward a more comprehensive declaration.
</P>
<P>
Senator Idris Abubakar confirmed after the committee session
that elaborate debates on the list could not begin until
identified documents are supplied. In the interim, however, he
said 37 names are ideal in the interest of adequate
representation for all 36 states and the capital.
</P>
<P>
Senator Gbenga Aluko said the matter had to be discussed at the
 committee of the whole Senate for transparency reasons. If it
were in a few member committee, suspicions over bribery could be
the order of the day, he added.
</P>
<P>
He reminded the Senate that it has been agreed that the
constitutional requirements for a ministerial nominee has to be
met. This requirement stipulates compliance with House of
Representatives membership election conditions including 30 years
minimum age, school certificate minimum educational
qualification, representation from a state and sponsorship by a
political party. 
</P>
