<HEADLINE> Sweet Piano Tunes By Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 17 (Xinhua) -- As many as 200 piano players aged
from 5 to 59 staged a combined performance of some China's best
loved musical pieces Tuesday morning in Longgang Town in east
China's Zhejiang Province, the largest performance of its kind
ever in the country.
</P>
<P>
The "Guinness Book of Records" piano performance, accompanied
by a grand chorus of 200 vocalists, was to highlight the brand new
look of the town, which has evolved from a small, barren fishing
village into a booming industrial and trade port economy since
1984.
</P>
<P>
The great changes which have taken place in the small town
epitomize the achievements and success of China's reform and
opening-up drive which began in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Longgang Town generated 2.3 billion yuan in GDP,
with income for per capita averaging at over 7,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Since 1984, the local government has placed great emphasis on
harmonizing local economic and cultural development, making it
possible for such piano performances to blossom resulting in today
's event which advances local ethical and cultural progress.
</P>
<P>
Longgang is now the top piano owning towns in China with local
farmers owning a total of 1,200. During recent years, more than 45
piano performances and contests have been held locally.
</P>
<P>
And local farmer Li Haicheng has also founded a piano school,
which already boasts a number of graduates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
