<HEADLINE> Japanese Aid Worker Attacked by Shark in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A Japanese foreign aid
worker in Tanzania has been attacked by a shark while he was
surfing in the Indian Ocean, a Tanzanian newspaper said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese International Co-operation Agency (JICA) worker,
only identified as Sudo, had three fingers bitten by the fierce
shark but managed to escape, The Express said.
</P>
<P>
A JICA official in Dar es Salaam confirmed the incident
Thursday, but she refused to give details.
</P>
<P>
Sudo was reportedly surfing in the sea area close to the
Oysterbay Hotel in the city on June 5. After the incident, he
took a chartered flight to South Africa for a surgery.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian authorities have warned people especially
students not to venture out in the sea area, the weekly newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
The number of reported shark attacks worldwide a year is said
to be below 100. 
</P>
