<HEADLINE> Chinese Trade Minister Meets British Secretary of State (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese trade minister Shi
Guangsheng met with visiting British Secretary of State for Trade
and Industry Stephen Byers here on Thursday, the first meeting
with a senior British official since NATO's suspension of air
strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The two exchanged views on trade between China and the United
Kingdom, between China and the European Union and on China's
accession to the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Shi noted that Sino-UK relations have improved much since Hong
Kong's return to China. The economic and trade relations between
the two countries, in particular, has grown at a speed higher than
that with other European nations.
</P>
<P>
"The leaders of our two countries have exchanged visits
frequently and that has greatly helped push forward bilateral
economic and trade ties," said the Chinese minister. "The
development of China-UK trade and economic relations is in the
fundamental interests of both countries and the world's peace and
development as well."
</P>
<P>
Shi said that from a long term perspective, trade and economic
relations between China and the European Union has great
development potential, but there are problems to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
The British side, while underlining its export levels to China,
should also pay attention to China's exports to Britain, he said,
adding that Britain can also play an active role in trade
liberalization as against the trade restrictions and protectionism
now rising in the EU.
</P>
<P>
Shi proposed that in the further expansion of economic and
trade relations between China and Britain and between China and
the EU, each party should open the commodities and service trade
market to the other.
</P>
<P>
He said that China and Britain can further diversify their
cooperation in the area of trade, investment, economic and
technological projects and the capital market. The two should also
utilize the joint commission system to resolve trade disputes. (
more)
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
