<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Trade Minister Meets British Secretary of State (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Byers offered on behalf of the British Government "its profound
distress and apologies" for NATO's attack on the Chinese embassy
in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said that the British Government supports China
's accession to the WTO at an early date, adding that Britain "
strongly" holds that China's entry before the WTO Seattle meeting
in the coming autumn is conducive.
</P>
<P>
Shi said that China has never changed its stance, viewpoint and
attitude toward its accession to the WTO. He stressed that China
can only join the WTO as a developing country, and the obligations
it should undertake must be in compliance with China's current
national strength.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, it is not the proper time now to resume the WTO
talks with either the United States or the European Union.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S.-led missile attack against the Chinese embassy in
Belgrade has damaged the good atmosphere of negotiations," he said.
"Only after the U.S.-led NATO has made a response satisfactory to
China and a good atmosphere is reinstated, the talks can be
resumed."
</P>
<P>
The minister said that China's accession to the WTO is demanded
in the first instance by China's process of reform and opening to
the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said that entrepreneurs from Britain and other
parts of the world have been welcome to engage in trade,
investment and other economic cooperation events, and they are and
will be welcome in the future.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by several top executive officers of large British
companies, Byers arrived here Wednesday night at the invitation of
the Chinese trade minister.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in China, Byers will visit relevant Chinese
ministries, and travel to Kunming on June 19 to attend the British
Day of the on-going 1999 International Horticultural Exposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
