<HEADLINE> Former U.N. Envoy Visits Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Three months after he left Angola
where the civil war was renewed, regretfully, former U.N. special
envoy Issa Diallo returned here Thursday for a visit.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Angolan Foreign Ministry said, Diallo's
current three- day visit to Angola is to discuss, on behalf of the
United Nations, with the Angolan authorities the country's grim
humanitarian situation.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival in the Luanda International Airport, Diallo
told the press that the United Nations "has not forgotten Angola"
and will continue its efforts in solving the armed conflicts in
the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is "very worried" about the humanitarian
situation in Angola, he said, adding that it believed that the
current political, military and humanitarian difficulties will be
overcome through "certain appropriate means."
</P>
<P>
Diallo was appointed the U.N. special envoy to Angola last year
to take the place of Alioune Blondin Beye who had died in a plane
accident.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations ended its observer mission in Angola in
February this year following Angolan government's accusation of
the poor performance on the part of U.N. peacekeeping forces and
its insistence of armed settlement with the opposition National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Diallo therefore left here on March 15.
</P>
<P>
With the stalemate in the Angolan crisis, more people at home
and abroad are calling for peaceful dialog between the Angolan
government and the UNITA. Observers here believe that Diallo's
present visit to Angola has much to do with this particular
backdrop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
