<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Meeting on Nigerian Oil Hub Crisis Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A peace meeting to find a lasting
solution to the crisis in Warri, a petroleum industry hub in south
Nigeria, kicked off in Asaba, capital of the Delta state
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which was presided by Governor James Ibori drew
representatives of the three ethnic groups, Ijaw, Itsekiri, and
Urhobo, local media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the peace talks, Ibori reminded the
participants that losses sustained were not only to the
inhabitants of Warri and its environs but also to the federal and
state governments.
</P>
<P>
The governor said that the present administration would not
allow the crisis to continue without resolution, appealing to the
participants to imbibe the spirit of give-and-take so that an
amicable solution could be found.
</P>
<P>
He commended the delegates for the maturity exhibited during
the visit of President Olusegun Obasanjo and urged them to heed
the president's appeal by coming together to iron out their
differences.
</P>
<P>
The governor urged them to give peace a chance so that
government could execute the development plans to make Warri a
true "oil city".
</P>
<P>
He said that "posterity would not forgive us if we do not
plough back our oil money into the development of Warri and indeed
Delta State."
</P>
<P>
He urged the delegates of the three ethnic communities to speak
frankly as the Warri crisis talks more within the purview of the
state government.
</P>
<P>
The youths of the ethnic communities had been undertaken severe
fighting till a curfew and shoot-at-sight were announced one week
ago in the battered city of Warri.
</P>
<P>
Governor Ibori had unveiled a disarmament package over the
weekend, offering cash and job opportunities for the surrender of
arms, which had encountered a cold reaction from the three ethnic
communities.
</P>
<P>
The governor also promised in his peace plan to set up a Warri
Urban Development Authority to address the roots of the
decades-old conflicts in the region.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo had pleaded for time to enable his government to
resolve the underlying problems behind the Warri crisis when he
visit the city last Friday after ethnic clashes has claimed about
300 lives.
</P>
<P>
The Niger delta region generates most of the country's oil and
above 90 percent of the country's foreign currency reserve, yet
find itself struggling in deep poverty.
</P>
<P>
Wide spread unemployment, and deep poverty are blamed to be the
roots of the frequent and rampant conflicts in the region, while
Idle youths kidnapping oil company personnel and warring with each
other are commonplace in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria President Highlights Partnership With S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
has stressed the "strategic partnership" between the most populous
country and South Africa, the most developed one in Africa.
</P>
<P>
After attending the inauguration of Thabo Mbeki as South
Africa's new president in Pretoria, Obasanjo told the press in
Johannesburg Wednesday that Nigeria regarded South Africa as a
desired partner and companion in " realizing the African dream."
</P>
<P>
"There is no competition between Nigeria and S. Africa, we need
 cooperation and feel it is necessary for the benefit of the
entire citizenry of both countries," the New Nigerian newspaper
Thursday quoted Obasanjo as saying.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo told a gathering of both countries' business
communities in Pretoria Tuesday that time is now ripe for South
African businessmen to collaborate with their Nigerian
counterparts for the general good of the continent.
</P>
<P>
"The continent is like a large basket whose hands are located
in west Africa, and to lift it up, you need the support of the two
hands which our countries provide," said the president.
</P>
<P>
He said that with democracy now in place in both countries,
they should come together, adding that "with the demise of
ruthless dictatorship in my country and the death of apartheid
here, our doors are both open for greater collaboration."
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian president stressed that the two peoples could
complement each other to bring investments to their countries,
assuring that measures are currently being taken to remove all
obstacles and ensure conducive climate for investors.
</P>
<P>
There are lots of advantages for potential investors in
Nigeria, listed among others, a large market and very cheap labor.
</P>
<P>
Inviting South Africans to come and invest, the president said
that as part of government's determination to liberalize the
economy it has commenced moves to privatize some of its key
sectors, including electricity supply and communications.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo returned to Nigerian capital Abuja Wednesday night
after concluding a two-day trip to South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
