<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, India Sign Final Accord on Bus Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh and India signed an
official and final agreement to start commercial operation of
Dhaka-Calcutta direct bus service here Thursday afternoon, ahead
of a scheduled two-day visit of Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari
Vajpayee to Bangladesh beginning Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed by Karar Mahmudul Hasan, joint secretary
of the Communication Ministry of Bangladesh, and K.R. Bhatti,
joint secretary of the Surface Transport Ministry of India,
completing all legal formalities to introduce the much-awaited bus
service.
</P>
<P>
The Indian cabinet approved the draft agreement Tuesday,
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Hasina and Vajpayee, who is to arrive here Saturday morning by
air from New Delhi, will receive two buses from Calcutta, capital
of the West Bengal state of India, to mark the inauguration of the
direct bus service.
</P>
<P>
The bus service will formally start before June 29, Hasan told
reporters after the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The two-year agreement will be reviewed after three months of
trial operation, during which two buses will leave from or come to
Dhaka every day except Sunday, Hasan said.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,000 visas are issued by India to Bangladeshis every
day, and as a result, the number of buses to be plying the route
will increase to 30 or more each day in six months to one year, he
said. Most of the buses will be run by the private sector, he
added.
</P>
<P>
More than 500,000 people travel by this route to and from
Bangladesh each year, a press release said.
</P>
<P>
After an initial agreement Hasan and Bhatti signed in the
Indian capital New Delhi in February this year, a trial bus left
Dhaka for Calcutta on April 6 and an Indian bus came to Dhaka on
April 8.  The two sides signed a protocol for the final
agreement in Dhaka on April 9.
</P>
<P>
The round-trip passenger fare on this route will be 1,100 taka
(22 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
