<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Insists Separate Sector for Russia in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 17 (Xinhua) -- President Boris Yeltsin insisted
Thursday that Russia should have a separate sector for its
peacekeepers in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with his Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev earlier Thursday, Yeltsin voiced his "categorical
disagreement" with Russia not being assigned a sector in Kosovo,
Federal Security Service Director Vladimir Putin said before a
meeting with Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev is holding talks with his U.S. counterpart, William
Cohen, in Helsinki, Finland, on Russia's peacekeeping role in
Kosovo and both talked of progress at the end of their last
session late Thursday. The two defense chiefs are expected to
resume negotiations Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said most of the issues have been settled amiably in
Helsinki. But the main question of assigning sectors has not,
Putin said.
</P>
<P>
"They don't want to give Russia a sector (in Kosovo). So I
warned Sergeyev that he should tell his opposite numbers at the
talks that it has been reported to the president. The president
categorically disagrees and will seek ways to oppose this," Putin
quoted Yeltsin as saying.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that he would discuss with Putin how things "will
end in Yugoslavia," how the U.N., Russia and the U.S. visualize
the future course of developments in and around Kosovo, the
Interfax news agency reported. 
</P>
