<HEADLINE> Philippines' Customs Revenue Up in First Five Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' Bureau of Customs
(BOC) reported Thursday that it collected 30.822 billion pesos
(771 million U.S. dollars) in the first five months, which was
three percent higher than the 29.920 billion pesos (748 million
U.S. dollars) of the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Customs Commissioner Nelson Tan said BOC surpassed its revenue
target by 1.2 percent over its target of 30.470 billion pesos (762
million U.S. dollars) set for the five-month period.
</P>
<P>
In May alone, the Bureau collected 7.738 billion pesos (193
million U.S. dollars), a hefty increase of 29 percent compared to
the 5.469 billion pesos (137 million U.S. dollars) revenue take a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Tan attributed the consistent upward trend in the revenue
mainly to the all out efforts of the men and women of the Bureau
to meet this year's target of 87.561 billion pesos (2.2 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
