<HEADLINE> Militants Sentenced for Plotting Raid in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's Higher Military Court on
Thursday sentenced four Islamic militants to life imprisonment
with hard labor for plotting to storm a presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
The court sentenced 16 other militants to prison terms of five
to 15 years with hard labor, the country's Middle East News Agency
(MENA) reported, adding that one of the 21 accused was acquitted
by the court.
</P>
<P>
The militants had been charged with plotting a sea-borne raid
in 1996 on the Montazah Presidential Palace in the Mediterranean
port city of Alexandria, 220 kilometers northwest of Cairo, MENA
said.
</P>
<P>
The men belonged to the outlawed al-Gamaa al-Islamiya, or
Islamic Group, Egypt's biggest militant group, the news agency
said.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Muslim extremists launched an insurrection in 1992 in
an attempt to overthrow the secular government and replace it with
a strictly Islamic rule. At least 1,200 people, mainly policemen
and militants, died in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, militants opened fire on Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak's car while he was visiting Ethiopia. He escaped the
assassination attempt unharmed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
