<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF to Support Structural Reforms in Asia: Fischer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) will continue to do everything it can to support the
continuation of the process of structural reform in Asian
economies, Stanley Fischer, first deputy managing director of the
IMF, said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The origins of the Asian financial crisis lay primarily in
capital account and financial sector problems, exacerbated in
several countries by inappropriate exchange rate policies, and
triggered by rapid outflows of capital, said Fischer, when
delivering a keynote speech at the 6th Far Eastern Economic Review
annual conference.
</P>
<P>
"Thus, policies adopted by governments to deal with the crisis,
in many cases with IMF support, had to be comprehensive to resolve
structural as well as macro problems," Fischer noted.
</P>
<P>
Of course, the structural reforms, especially in the banking
and corporate sectors, are not complete in any country, for this
is a long-term task, he said.
</P>
<P>
"But it was important to begin as soon as possible -- and
looking around the region, we see that the countries that moved
most rapidly on structural reforms are also those that are
recovering most rapidly," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said that one important risk now is that the burgeoning
recovery in crisis-struck economies will reduce the urgency of
reform, and allow complacency, or normal politics, to set in. Much
structural reform remains to be carried out in these countries, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Fischer noted that Japan's recovery is very important for this
region. This applies not only to the recovery of output growth,
but also to the strengthening of the banking system, to ensure the
revival of Japanese private sector capital flows to the region.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, actions taken to recapitalize the banks last year
in Japan are beginning to pay off, Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis has made it very clear that the
international financial system has to be strengthened, said
Fischer. The international community will continue to rely on the
IMF to play its central role in the international system.
</P>
<P>
"We do this through surveillance, lending policies, as an
institution providing the machinery for consultation and
collaboration on international monetary problems," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
