<HEADLINE> Indian PM to Pay "Goodwill Visit" to Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari
Vajpayee will come to Bangladesh for a two-day "goodwill visit"
beginning Saturday, Foreign Ministry officials said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The highlight of the visit will be the ceremonial inauguration
of the Dhaka-Calcutta bus service on Saturday, and Foreign
Ministry officials described the visit of Vajpayee, who is now
caretaker prime minister, as "a goodwill visit."
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee, who will arrive here by air in the morning,
accompanied by External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh and Foreign
Secretary K. Raghunath, will hold talks with his Bangladeshi
counterpart, Sheikh Hasina, before jointly receiving two Indian
buses carrying nearly 80 passengers from Calcutta, West Bengal, in
the afternoon, Foreign Secretary Shafi Sami told reporters at the
regular weekly news briefing.
</P>
<P>
The inauguration of the direct bus service "is very important"
for the about 1.2 billion people of the two countries, at least
for those who travel between Dhaka and Calcutta, Joint Secretary
of the Communication Ministry Karar Mahmudul Hasan told a separate
press conference. Hasan and K.R. Bhatti, joint secretary of the
Surface Transport Ministry of India, signed an official agreement
on the bus service here on Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Indian premier may take the opportunity to discuss with
Hasina economic issues including port and transit facilities, and
geopolitical matters of common concern, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Indian side may also raise the sensitive issue of
purchasing natural gas though pipeline while Bangladesh will
insist on obtaining zero tariff facility on all its export items
to India. Both the ruling and the opposition have announced
objection to exporting gas before "meeting domestic demands."
</P>
<P>
Dhaka is likely to propose setting up of joint venture
industries in Bangladesh with "buy-back arrangements," in an
effort to bridge the huge trade gap, which is in Delhi's favor,
</P>
<P>
This will be Vajpayee's second visit to Bangladesh in two
decades. He came to Dhaka in the late 1970s as foreign minister.
</P>
