<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Currency Hits New Low Against US Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Somali currency hit its
lowest Thursday as it scratched 10, 000 shillings against one U.S.
dollar, down from 9,500 shillings to one dollar after the second
consignment of bank notes arrived in Mogadishu early this month.
</P>
<P>
The Somali currency valued at 8,500 shillings to dollar before
the consignments of bank notes arrived in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 billion Somali shillings worth of over 9.5 million
dollars printed in Canada have been brought to Mogadishu on three
installments since last month.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, now there is some hope that the shilling can again
gain grounds against the hard currencies despite its continuous
devaluation.
</P>
<P>
A vessel transporting more than 50,000 crates of banana sailed
for the Gulf countries two days ago for the first time in the
last two years.
</P>
<P>
The livestock dealers have also started going to the
countryside to buy goats and sheep for export following the lift
of the ban against Somalia's animals last month.
</P>
<P>
The banana and livestock exports are two major exported items
of Somalia, giving a real encouragement to the shilling.
</P>
<P>
However, life is becoming extremely difficult for many Somalis
because of the inflow of the overseas printed Somali shillings
into the local markets, increasing banditry and the raging civil
strive for control of such towns as Baidoa and Kismaio.
</P>
<P>
The illegally imported money by Somali businessmen and faction
leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid have caused a serious inflation,
further devastating the already meager economy of the
war-prolonged Horn of Africa country.
</P>
<P>
The souring inflation is affecting almost all of the
commodities available for sale in the main markets, especially the
imported goods and food stuffs.
</P>
<P>
The ordinary Somali families are now depending on such local
food products as maize, beans and sorghum which are not yet
affected by the inflation.
</P>
<P>
But the sale of these products themselves are at risk since the
business movement in the Bay and Bakol regions are now restricted
by the recent capture of Baidoa town by the Rahanwein Resistance
Army which is allegedly backed by the Ethiopian forces.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Baidoa town indicate that the life is becoming
unbearable and expensive as a result of its isolation from capital
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
All kinds of communications including the traffic movement from
 Mogadishu to those regions have been stopped after the fall of
Baidoa some ten days ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia PDI-P Leads With 34.07 Pct in Vote Counting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Democratic Party of
Struggle (PDI-P) led by Megawati Soekarnoputri has maintained its
lead over the other 47 parties in the vote counting Thursday by
grabbing 30.69 million votes.
</P>
<P>
According to unofficial results collected by the official
Antara News Agency from provincial chapters of the Indonesian
Election Committee (PPI), the PDI-P collected 34.07 percent of the
votes counted until Thursday afternoon, followed by ruling Golkar
Party 19.57 million votes (21.72 percent), National Awakening
Party (PKB) 12.36 million votes (13.73 percent), United
Development Party (PPP) 9.39 million votes (10.42 percent),
National Mandate Party (PAN) 6.24 million votes (6.93 percent),
Crescent Star Party 1.68 million votes (1.87 percent), Justice
Party 1.04 million votes (1.16 percent), and the Justice and Unity
Party (PKP) 897,440 votes (1 percent).
</P>
<P>
The data showed that by Thursday afternoon, 40 of the 48
political parties contesting the June 7 elections got less than
one percent of the total votes.
</P>
<P>
A total of 90.1 million votes out of the 117.8 million
registered votes have been counted so far.
</P>
<P>
PDI-P collected the largest number of votes in 11 provinces,
namely, North Sumatera, South Sumatera, Lampung, Jakarta, West
Java, Central Java, Yogyakarta, Bali, East Kalimantan, Central
Kalimantan and Maluku.
</P>
<P>
Golkar meanwhile recorded victory in 14 provinces, namely, West
Sumatera, Riau, Jambi, Bengkulu, West Nusa Tenggara, East Nusa
Tenggara, East Timor, South Kalimantan, West Kalimantan, North
Sulawesi, South Sulawesi, Central Sulawesi, Southeast Sulawesi and
Irian Jaya.
</P>
<P>
PPP won the largest number of votes in Aceh and PKB in East
Java.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, official data collected by the General Election
Commission (KPU), based on votes counted till Thursday afternoon,
showed PDI-P in the lead with 18.59 million votes, followed by PKB
(9.3 million), Golkar (8.5 million), PPP (4.778 million) and PAN
(3.36 million).
</P>
<P>
KPU officials stressed that the results of the election will be
determined by the official data issued by KPU, and other data are
unofficial.
</P>
<P>
Forty-eight political parties took part in the election last
week to compete for 462 out of the 500 seats in the House of
Representatives (DPR). The remaining 38 seats are reserved for the
military, whose members do not vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
