<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fuel Shortage Hits Zambian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The diesel shortage which has
persistently hit Zambian capital Lusaka continued Thursday with
nearly all the service stations in the city operating without oil.
</P>
<P>
The persistent fuel shortage has temporarily crippled
operations at the University Teaching Hospital, the biggest
hospital in the southern African country, police and many other
government departments.
</P>
<P>
At the hospital mortuary, an attendant said that few vehicles
had gone to collect corpses, causing congestion in the
refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
"Corpses are currently being piled on top of each other since
people just come with excuses that there is no transport to pick
their relatives due to the fuel shortage," said the attendant.
</P>
<P>
A check at the police main filling point found out that all the
diesel tanks try with only a few liters of premium.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman, Alex Chilufya, described the prevailing
situation as chaotic and called for a quick solution to the
problem.
</P>
<P>
He said only urgent cases will be attended to due to the
limited resources available.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has been advised to involve all the
oil marketing companies in the importation of refined products to
ease the fuel blues in the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Vice-President of Zambia Association of Chambers of
Commerce and Industry (ZACCI), Boniface Chiweza, has called on the
government to allow all oil marketing companies to bring in the
fuel.
</P>
<P>
"Our economy has been liberalized and the government should
therefore allow individual oil marketing companies to import the
fuel rather than have it brought in through the Zambia National
Oil Company," he said.
</P>
<P>
The association was worried about the fuel shortage because it
had come at a time when transporters were supposed to be ferrying
this season's maize harvest from the areas of production.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Truckers Association of Zambia, Charles Madondo
said that the one million liters of fuel recently imported by the
government was only about a day's consumption as long distance
truckers required as much as 1,500 liters on a single trip.
</P>
<P>
He said oil marketing companies should share the contract
instead of awarding the tender to only one company as government
initially did early this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
