<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Trees Planted in China in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- China planted trees on an area of
4.7 million hectares last year, increasing the total forest area
to 130 million ha, according to China's latest environmental
situation report.
</P>
<P>
The annual report issued by the State Environmental Protection
Administration (SEPA) says the forest coverage rate is nearly 14
percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China closed hillsides of nine million ha to
facilitate afforestation. And about 2.2 billion trees were planted
by Chinese volunteers last year.
</P>
<P>
China is going ahead smoothly with its forest shelterbelt
constructions in northwest, north and northeast China, the middle
and lower reaches of the Yangtze River and the coastal regions,
with more than 2.23 million ha of trees planted in those areas
last year, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report said China planted 327,000 ha of forests in the
middle reaches of the Yellow River, and the valleys of Liaohe
River, Pearl River and Huaihe River last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the report showed that the per capita forest share in
China is 0.11 ha, 17.2 percent of the world average.
</P>
<P>
Last year, more than 4,400 fires damaged about 27,000 ha of
forests, and seven million ha of forests suffered from plant
diseases.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
