<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soil Erosion Control, Arable Land Protection Speeded up in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- China successfully controlled soil
erosion over an area of more than 50,000 square kilometers last
year, according to the latest environmental situation report.
</P>
<P>
The annual report released by the State Environmental
Protection Administration (SEPA) says the country had succeeded in
conserving water and soil over a total area of 78 million hectares
by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
China has also built terraced fields and dams and turned
deserts into farmland, covering about 12 million hectares and
planted 40 million hectares of forests, says the report.
</P>
<P>
Water conservation authorities last year increased their water
storage capacity by 25 billion cubic meters, holding back 1.5
billion tons of sand and earth.
</P>
<P>
Several key projects to conserve water and prevent soil erosion
are now underway along China's major rivers, including the Yangtze,
Yellow and Pearl rivers. Both the central and local governments
have increased investment in water and soil conservation.
</P>
<P>
However, the report says China's arable land decreased by 261,
000 hectares last year, 126,000 hectares more than in 1997.
</P>
<P>
China revised its laws and regulations on land management last
year and using arable land for non-agricultural purposes has been
banned since 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
