<HEADLINE> Nigerian President Vows to Stop Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
has vowed to stop the rampant corruption in the west African
country.
</P>
<P>
After attending the inauguration of Thabo Mbeki as South
Africa's new president in Pretoria, Obasanjo told the press in
Johannesburg Wednesday that any public official who steals or
misappropriates public funds will be disgraced and made to face
the wrath of the law.
</P>
<P>
While noting his role in the formation of the anti-corruption
group, Transparency International, Obasanjo restated his
commitment to bringing corruption to an end in his country,
Nigeria's The Guardian newspaper Thursday reported.
</P>
<P>
The president praised the regime of former Head of State
General Abdulsalam Abubakar, for taking steps to recover
ill-gotten wealth from public officials.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo said that more than 800 million U.S. dollars had been
recovered while private properties acquired corruptly had been
confiscated both in Nigeria and abroad.
</P>
<P>
The president restated his resolve to continue with the task as
well as initiate new procedures for recovering wealth looted from
the federal treasury.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of human rights, Obasanjo said that violations
committed between the last democratic dispensation and now would
be investigated to address the plight of those who suffered
unjustly in the past.
</P>
<P>
The Panafrican News Agency Sunday cited a survey of the
Transparency International as showing that Nigeria lists itself
in the top of the World' s 23 most bribery-rampant country.
</P>
<P>
The Berlin-based organization suggested in its survey that the
prevalence of corruption appears to deter the foreign investment
in these countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
