<HEADLINE> Poppy Seeds As Food Additive Banned in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Health has
banned food manufacturers from using poppy seeds as an additive in
foodstuffs after an illegal practice was disclosed.
</P>
<P>
An urgent circular issued by the ministry urged local
departments responsible for food hygiene supervision to "fully
investigate and deal with cases of using poppy seeds in food
preparation", warning that certain elements found in poppies may
do harm to human health and cause addiction.
</P>
<P>
A Henan based food company supplying fried chicken nationwide
was discovered recently to be adding poppy seeds in food
processing materials, and traces of morphine and other elements
were detected, according to today's Health News.
</P>
<P>
China prohibited food suppliers from adding any poppy parts to
foodstuffs such as soup and noodles in 1991. However, the illegal
practice has not been wiped out because some people believe
poppies can make food more delicious.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices End Higher on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Share Prices rose modestly on
Singapore Stock Market Thursday as later profit-taking pared early
gains made on the back of Wall Street's rise and retail investor
interest in second liners.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) gained 13.54 points in
active trading to end at 2,057.34 points, off from its intraday
high of 2,080.93 points.
</P>
<P>
Total volume extended to 1,310.77 million shares valued at
1,239.03 million Singapore dollars (727.43 million U.S. dollars).
Advancers outpaced decliners by 275 to 68 with 99 counters
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Eagle, a Chinese township enterprise manufacturing ceramic
sanitary wares and tiles, topped the volume list with 106.86
million units changing hand. It was followed by ICT that chalked
up 86.79 million units. Dragon was the next with a turnover of
66.11 million counters.
</P>
<P>
CityDev and DBS F were the top movers as they ran up 60 cents
to close at 11.70 and 17.90 Singapore dollars respectively.
Venture climbed up 50 cents to finish at 13.10 Singapore dollars.
C &AMP; C gained 45 cents to end at 10.00 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, SPH headed the descent of the day as it
incurred a loss of 60 cents to close at 27.50 Singapore dollars.
UOB F sank 40 cents to finish at 11.40 Singapore dollars. SPH 100
retreated 30 cents to end at 27.70 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the overnight rally on Wall Street was triggered
by the tame U.S. May inflation data released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The optimism that the U.S. inflation is in check relieved
investors' fear of possible rise in U.S interest rates and further
fueled the already bullish mood in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that gains in key index-linked stocks boosted
the STI although retail stocks continued to weigh heavily on the
market sentiment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
