<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pollution Endangers Future of Humanity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Even though population control
remains a top priority in China's development agenda declining
male virility, which is a worldwide phenomena, is posing a serious
threat to the country's demographic future.
</P>
<P>
Environmental changes induced by wide use of man-made chemicals
are blamed for falling semen quality over the past two decades,
according to today's China Youth Daily.
</P>
<P>
Recent research based on the statistical analysis of 11,726
samples obtained from examinations of semen quality nationwide
between 1981 and 1996 shows that the average amount of semen and
the total number of sperm from each ejaculation has dramatically
dropped by 10.3 percent and 30.6 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The research was conducted by scientists with the State Family
Planning Commission, the central government body in charge of
population control and improvement of reproductive health.
</P>
<P>
Their findings show that the situation is actually much worse
in cities and the more industrialized zones than in the
countryside and less developed areas.
</P>
<P>
"Pollution is closely related to the worsening semen quality,"
said Zhang Shucheng, one of the researchers.
</P>
<P>
"Animal tests have demonstrated that among the 100 known
chemical compounds, more than half of them are harmful to sperm,"
he explained. Scientists have proved that certain chemicals are
the direct cause of falling fertility and even for the extinction
of certain species like certain amphibians, fishes and birds.
</P>
<P>
They agree that the more sensitive reproductive cells are the
prime victims of newly invented compounds in the course of
industrial development, and declining male virility has
contributed to an increase in the rate of infertility,
miscarriages, abnormalities in new-borns, and sexual abnormalities
and handicaps among the young in China.
</P>
<P>
At least 100,000 man-made compounds are used worldwide, and the
long term effects of about 40 percent still remain unknown. The
influence of pollution on the human reproductive system may prove
to be the biggest challenge for human health in the 21st century,
some scientists assert.
</P>
<P>
Falling semen quality is a topic of global concern. According
to an analysis of published reports from 21 countries by Danish
scientists, the number of sperm for each ejaculation fell over 40
percent and 20 percent respectively between 1938 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
To ascertain the relationship between environmental changes and
the declining semen quality, Zhang and his colleagues are seeking
funds for new research into the cause and effect of the
environment on semen quality.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Many Injured in Bomb Explosion in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Many passengers were critically
injured Thursday morning when a bomb exploded in a bus at
Eheliyagoda in Sabaragamuwa province, over 70 kilometers from
Colombo, police said.
</P>
<P>
Police said the bus left Colombo for Badulla in Uva province
Wednesday night. The explosion occurred at around 1:15 a.m.
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At the time of the explosion, the bus was packed to capacity,
and many passengers had jumped out of the windows in panic, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
police pointed out that among the passengers there was a
soldier suspected to have carried a bomb in his bag. They
suspected that the bomb might have gone off by accident.
</P>
<P>
Government analysts and police officers left Colombo to the
scene of the explosion Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
The injured were rushed to Eheliyagoda hospital. Among them
were several women and an infant who were seriously injured, the
police said, adding that a team of police officers are probing the
accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
