<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrea Downs Another 2 Ethiopian Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Eritrean Foreign Ministry said
in Asmara Thursday that the Eritrean troops shot down two
Ethiopian Mig-23 fighters Wednesday afternoon on the Mereb-Setit
front.
</P>
<P>
A news release from the ministry said that the two Mig aircraft
were hit at high-altitude as they encroached on Eritrean airspace
and fell behind Ethiopian front line.
</P>
<P>
Previously, two Ethiopian Mig-23 fighter planes and one Mi-35
helicopter gun ship were shot down on Sunday and last Friday
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that "ground fighting in the Mereb-Setit
front, which continued with less intensity in the past two days,
resumed Thursday morning."
</P>
<P>
The ministry also said that Ethiopian cumulative losses were
over 18,000 killed or wounded in the intense border battles from
June 10 to 14, although the figures for the past two days were not
available yet.
</P>
<P>
However, Ethiopia Wednesday claimed that its troops had put
21,000 Eritrean soldiers out of action in recent six days of
fighting.
</P>
<P>
War broke out in early May 1998 along the 1,000-kilometer
borders of the two Horn of African neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Although both nations have agreed to the peace framework put
forward by the Organization of African Unity (OAU), they differed
over the details of the peace plan and its implementation.
</P>
</TEXT>
