<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai FM On East Asia's Overall Structural Readjustment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan Thursday urged East Asia, particularly Southeast Asia, to
rethink its strategy of growth and give priority to overall
structural readjustment.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 6th Annual Conference of the Far Eastern
Economic Review here, Surin said that East Asia cannot remain
dependent on outside capital, technology and management as in the
past.
</P>
<P>
The region shall invest heavily on human resource development,
science and technology, research and design for new products, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The region will have to develop diverse and varied centers of
growth over a wider geographical spread and a larger spectrum of
sectors and disciplines," he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that ASEAN economies have for the past three
decades been an extension of other economies, rather than being
independent, with home-grown capital, technology and management.
</P>
<P>
"To achieve sustainable long-term growth, the region must
bolster home-bred technology and management," he added.
</P>
<P>
"This is not to say that we should close ourselves from outside
investment," said Surin. "We cannot avoid, and indeed we welcome,
economic integration and cooperation in a globalized world."
</P>
<P>
But, he said, each country and region will have to be able to
identify its own area of competency and seek to complement others
in areas where they have comparative advantages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Reshuffle in China's Insurance Intermediaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A major reshuffle is imminent in
China's insurance intermediary market, a top official of the China
Insurance Regulatory Commission (CIRC) revealed here today.
</P>
<P>
Tang Yunxiang, vice-chairman of the CIRC told Xinhua in an
interview that the first stage of the watchdog's drive to regulate
the market, in which all the insurance agents have to participate,
would be finished by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
He explained that in the next stage, all agents will undergo
examinations set by the watchdog and that those who failed would
not be allowed to operate.
</P>
<P>
According to CIRC figures, China now has about 220,000 part-
time insurance agents employing nearly 600,000 people, as well as
over 500,000 individual agents, most of them selling life
insurance.
</P>
<P>
So far there are no approved insurance brokers or professional
agents in China. However Tang disclosed that the CIRC would
approve their establishment in the near future, if the go-ahead is
given by the State Council.
</P>
<P>
To prepare for this, the supervisory authorities last year
promulgated draft regulations on the necessary qualifications
required.
</P>
<P>
Based on these regulations, on May 15 this year the CIRC held
the first national brokers' qualification examination. About 7,100
people sat for it.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Liu Jingsheng, a CIRC official in
charge of the intermediary sector said here today that there are
also plans to introduce loss adjusters although he gave no details.
</P>
<P>
Liu made the remarks at an international seminar on insurance
intermediaries, which opened here today and was attended by some
140 government officials and senior managers from major insurance
firms from China and abroad, as well as insurance experts and
scholars.
</P>
<P>
According to him, in 1998, more than 40 percent of the country'
s 49.9 billion yuan premium income for property insurance came
from agents, while over 80 percent of the 68.3 billion yuan
premium income for health and life insurance came from individual
salesmen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
