<HEADLINE> Seoul Informs Pyongyang of Delegation List for Beijing Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government Thursday
informed the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) of a
list of its delegation to be sent to Beijing for an inter-Korea
vice ministerial meeting next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The list was conveyed via a hot line between the liaison
offices of the inter-Korean Red Cross organizations at the truce
village of Panmunjom Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Seoul asked Pyongyang to deliver its delegation list
after its acceptance of the message despite the military clash
which took place in the Yellow Sea Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Seoul proposed in the message that the delegations meet at
Kempinski Hotel in Beijing at 10 a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Vice Unification Minister Yang Young-shik will
lead the three-member delegation to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, one day after the inter-Korean clash broke out,
the DPRK Committee of the Peaceful Reunification of the Fatherland
stated that it restricted or suspended the visits by South Koreans
to Pyongyang as well as contacts for the time being.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear whether the statement will affect the
forthcoming vice-ministerial talks slated for next Monday to
discuss issues on reunion of separated family members.
</P>
<P>
At around 11:30 a.m. Thursday, three South Korean ships loaded
with 30,000 tons of fertilizer have left the South Korean port of
Ulsan for the DPRK after a half-day delay, said the South Korean
National Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
A Defense Ministry spokesman said Thursday afternoon that there
were no special symptoms of mounting tension in the recent two
days.
</P>
<P>
The calm in the sea followed an armed conflict, in which one
DPRK torpedo boat was sunken and three others were seriously
damaged while two South Korean patrol ships were slightly damaged
and seven servicemen wounded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
