<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Forms Body to Address Dioxin Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
formed an inter-agency body to monitor developments and gather
information related to the dioxin contamination of feed and
identified food products that came from Belgium, Netherlands,
France and Germany.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Secretary Edgardo Angara said Thursday that he has
created an ad hoc committee consisting of concerned bureaus of the
departments of agriculture, health, trade and industry, as well as
representatives of meat companies and meat importers.
</P>
<P>
He instructed the committee to formulate recommendations on
further action to be taken in relation to Agriculture Department's
Administrative Order No. 23, which suspends importation of
identified products from the four European countries.
</P>
<P>
The order covers only in-transit shipments of skimmed milk and
frozen meat originating from EU (European Union) countries other
than Belgium.
</P>
<P>
According to the order, release of the product requires a
complementary certification for each shipment that the product
"originates solely from animals from farms, which have not used
Belgian products and is free from dioxin contamination."
</P>
<P>
For formulated or processed milk or meat products already on
the shelves, the order states that advisories that the
certification requirements have been met will be issued upon
submission of the said certification.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the certification that the product is "free from
dioxin contamination," Angara said in-transit shipments of Belgian
skimmed milk and meat will need data results of laboratory
analysis ruling out dioxin contamination.
</P>
<P>
He said the ad hoc committee will continue to monitor relevant
developments in the European Union and the action taken by other
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0198 </DOCNO>
