<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 09:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Crackdown on Immoral International Calls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has decided to
crackdown on the so-called friendship calls which, government
officials said, are both costly and immoral, a local newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"It is not illegal, but we have to protect the people from such
indecent services, especially young people who make most of the
calls," the Arab Times quoted director of the Telecom Department
at the Ministry of Communications Local Service Sector Mohammed
Al-Duaij as saying.
</P>
<P>
Al-Duaij said that the Ministry will cut off such "friendship"
lines with the technical capability it possesses.
</P>
<P>
Many subscribers, he said, approach the Ministry after
receiving huge bills for international calls, of which some
reached over 2,000 Kuwaiti dinars (6,600 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Usually made by male Kuwaitis aged between 16 to 25, the
international calls are made without the knowledge of parents who
are left with huge phone bills, he said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Duaij said some of the destinations of the "friendship"
calls, which increased since 1991 with the introduction of dialing
a joke service to Canada, are Jamaica, Chile, Moldova, Sierra
Leone as well as Canada.
</P>
<P>
It usually takes 20 to 25 minutes to make such a call.
</P>
<P>
"You will find there is bad conversations, indecent words
between boys and girls, because boys are seeking 'hot feelings'
from the other end," the official said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that these calls may lead teenagers to commit crimes
such as raping their housemaid, because they "have no ability to
start a marriage and build a family immediately." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
