<HEADLINE> French Troops Enter Northern Kosovo City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- French troops joining the U.N.
Kosovo peace keeping operation force (KFOR) began entering the
northern Kosovo city of Kosovska Mitrovica Thursday morning,
reported Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
The move, which was made two days ahead of schedule, could be
aimed at preventing the infiltration by the ethnic Albanian
guerrillas, the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA), into the city.
</P>
<P>
Serb forces will pull out of the city within a few days,
leaving to French control the city with a majority Serb population.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted Lieutenant Charles-Philippe d'Orleans, a spokesman
of French troops in Kosovo, as saying that KFOR soldiers were
entering the city by helicopters.
</P>
<P>
The Leclerc tanks of the French army left Macedonia for
northern Kosovo early Thursday morning, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 900 French soldiers unexpectedly rushed to northern Kosovo
by helicopters and armored vehicles on Wednesday from Gniljane in
southeast Kosovo, where they had been staying for several days.
</P>
<P>
The KLA has been trying to take over the vacuum of power as
Serb forces are pulling out the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
