<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Jute Mills to Lose 46.4 Mln Dollars in 1998-99 Fiscal Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The jute mills in Bangladesh are
going to incur a total loss of nearly 2.25 billion taka (46.4
million U.S. dollars) during the current July 1998-June 1999
fiscal year due to a sharp price gap between the production cost
and the export price of jute goods, an English newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Of the total amount, the loss by public-sector jute mills is
likely to stand at around 1.5 billion taka (30.9 million dollars)
while the loss by the private sector mills is at 0.75 billion taka
(15.5 million dollars), The Financial Express said, quoting
concerned sources.
</P>
<P>
All the jute mills of the country were nationalized by the
government after independence in 1971. They have been incurring
heavy losses since then, and the government had also shared the
losses by providing cash subsidy and loss-financing against jute
goods exports, they said.
</P>
<P>
In December 1982, 35 state-owned jute mills were handed over to
the private sector and another 32 mills remained under the
Bangladesh Jute Mills Corporation (BJMC).
</P>
<P>
During the period from 1972 to 1982, the government provided
950 million taka (19.6 million dollars) as cash subsidy, 820
million taka (16.9 million dollars) as export subsidy and 3.59
billion taka (74 million dollars) in the form of equity infusion.
</P>
<P>
Besides, under the Jute Sector Adjustment Credit Program
introduced by the World Bank, the country's jute mills received
9.46 billion taka (195.2 million dollars) in the form of
loss-financing from 1992 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
Tough competition in the world markets, increase in labor
wages, introduction of peak-hour electricity rate for the jute
mills, major devaluation of the Indian currency and higher
production cost than the export prices were responsible for losses
incurred by the jute mills, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
At present, the production costs of country's jute goods are
estimated at nearly 30 percent higher than their prices in the
international markets, they said.
</P>
<P>
A large number of looms both in public and private sector mills
had to be closed down over the years and many other are facing
closure.
</P>
<P>
Presently, some 12,000 out of the 16,000 looms in the MJMC
mills are in operation while the number of operational looms in
private sector mills are estimated at 4,500 against the previous
number of 9,500.
</P>
<P>
The prices of jute goods are showing a sharp downtrend in the
international markets over the past few years, and prices of jute
goods had declined by around four percent in 1998-99 fiscal year
compared to the previous one.
</P>
<P>
The price of exported jute goods during July-April of the
1998-99 fiscal year was recorded at 618.47 dollars per ton against
the price at 641.85 dollars in the last fiscal year, according to
statistics of Export Promotion Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Jute is Bangladesh's main cash crop, and as many as 25 percent
of the total population are involved with the jute-related
activities and around 250,000 workers are directly dependent on
jute, and another 100,000 traders also earn their livelihood from
jute business.
</P>
<P>
The jute sector is also a major foreign exchange earner of the
country, which fetches around 325 million dollars per annum from
exporting jute goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
