<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Burns Banned Fishing Nets to Protect Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has destroyed more
than 3, 900 banned fishing nets and punished a number of convicts
involved in a major crackdown on illegal fishing activities in
Lake Victoria, the largest one in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Ten people have been arrested and jailed, 25 others fined and
140 cases are still pending in court, Daily News reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The fishing gear included 3,105 under-five inch gill nets, 518
beach seine nets, 214 under-ten millimeter seine nets and
monofilament nets, worth 327.6 million shillings (about 460,000
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The action to burn the nets was supervised by the police and
fisheries officials Tuesday in the Mwanza Region on the southern
shore of the lake, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time for the Fisheries Department in Mwanza
Region to destroy illegal fishing gear which over-exploited
fishery resources in the lake, bordering Tanzania, Uganda and
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Eight months ago, the department destroyed banned fishing gear
worth 255. 7 million shillings in Mwanza, said the Mwanza Regional
Acting Fisheries Officer, William Fundi.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent research done by the Kenya Marine and
Fisheries Research Institute, over the last two decades, the
fishing gears used in the lake have become increasingly
non-selective.
</P>
<P>
In 1981, the most commonly caught Nile perch weighed about 50
to 100 kilograms. In 1996, the weight of a tail of such fish was
reduced to five and 10 kilograms, researchers said.
</P>
<P>
Fundi warned people to stop using illegal means for fishing as
the crackdown operation is still going on.
</P>
<P>
Unscrupulous fishermen have also been blasted for using
explosives and chemical substances for fishing, threatening the
eco-system of the lake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
