<P>
BEIRUT, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Three members of the pro-Israeli
South Lebanon Army (SLA) were wounded Thursday in Lebanese
guerrillas' attack in south Lebanon, the Voice of the People radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The three militiamen were hit by a roadside bomb detonated by
Lebanese guerrillas at Dier Saryan on the verge of the Israeli
occupied border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The militia also discovered another six bombs in the eastern
sector of the occupied zone, the radio quoted security sources as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, claimed
responsibility for the attack, saying its fighters launched a
series of operations, including bombing ambushes, against Israeli
occupation forces and SLA from Wednesday night till Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes raided suspected Hezbollah bases in Lebanon's
eastern area of West Bekaa Valley and villages on the verge of the
occupied zone in retaliation to Hezbollah's attacks.
</P>
<P>
There has been no immediate report of casualties from the air
blast.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting to dislodge Israeli forces and SLA
out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
