<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Tigers Move to Special Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, June 17 (Xinhua) --Seven rare South China tigers have
been relocated from Suzhou Zoo to a special breeding center on the
outskirts of the city in east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
 It is estimated there are now only 50 or more South China
tigers left in the world and they are actually closer to
extinction, a plight worse than the giant panda.
</P>
<P>
 The zoo's five remaining tigers will also be moved in a
couple of days to the center, which opened in January this year
and cost seven million yuan to construct.
</P>
<P>
 With a total area of four hectares, the breeding center
boasts the most up to date equipment and has 30 cages, as well as
extensive veterinary, research and monitoring facilities,
including 16 pick-up cameras, to keep checks on those tigers in
labour.
</P>
<P>
 Since 1988, more than 30 South China tigers have been bred
artificially in Suzhou Zoo, which is regarded as Number One
worldwide for its breeding skills involving endangered species.
</P>
<P>
More than half of South China tigers which now scatter around
other zoos throughout the country were born in Suzhou Zoo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
