<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Aquatic Product Exports Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's aquatic product exports in
the first five months of this year increased by 11.3 percent over
the same period of last year to 299.3 million U.S. dollars,
Vietnam's business newspaper The Saigon Times Daily reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam saw high export growth for such items as frozen fish
(30 percent), frozen cuttlefish (29 percent) and dried cuttlefish
(nearly 10 percent), the daily quoted an official of the Fishery
Ministry as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, exports of shrimps, a major foreign exchange earner,
dropped to 144 million dollars from 153 million dollars in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In the period, the United States imported 41.9 million dollars
worth of aquatic products from Vietnam, up from 23.4 million
dollars in the year-ago period, making it Vietnam's second biggest
aquatic product importer after Japan.
</P>
<P>
China's aquatic product imports from Vietnam surged from 7.3
million dollars to 17.3 million dollars and those of South Korea
from 2.2 million dollars to 12.2 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, aquatic product imports by European Union countries
plummeted to 34 million dollars from 40.6 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
If border trade is included, Vietnam's aquatic product exports
would total 82,350 tons worth 324 million dollars in the period, a
9-percent rise from the same period a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
