<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Threatens Kenyan Education: UNICEF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's education system is under
the threat from the HIV/AIDS scourge rampant in the country, an
official from the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) has
warned.
</P>
<P>
Helena Eversole, UNICEF representative in Kenya, said at a
ceremony to mark the Day of African Child on Wednesday that 22
percent of girls aged between 15 and 19 years in the east African
country are HIV positive.
</P>
<P>
This year's theme of the Day of the Africa Child declared by
the Organization of African Unity, focuses on the HIV/AIDS
scourge.
</P>
<P>
"It is undeniable that the entire education system of this
country is under the threat of HIV/AIDS," Eversole said, adding
that only four percent of boys within the same age group were
HIV-infected.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper Thursday quoted the UNICEF
official as saying that "pupils are infected, teachers are dying
at an alarming frequency and an increasing number of children can
not attend school because thousands of children orphaned by AIDS."
</P>
<P>
She also said that the UNICEF planned to fight HIV/AIDS through
teaching youth how to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Information and Broadcasting Minister Joseph Nyagah also
told the participants at the ceremony in capital Nairobi that the
number of AIDS orphans in the country was expected to reach
580,000 by 2000 and almost a million by 2005.
</P>
<P>
He noted that schools are among the most important institutions
in a child's life, calling for the introduction of a curriculum on
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Kenyan Health Permanent Secretary Philemon Mwaisaka
said that more than 200,000 adult Kenyans are expected to die this
year of AIDS, leaving behind thousands of children without
parental care or support. 
</P>
</TEXT>
