<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, June 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini on Wednesday
urged the Kosovar Liberation Army (KLA) to lay down its arms and
become a "political force."
</P>
<P>
In a statement to a joint session of the senate and lower house
foreign affairs committees, Dini noted that NATO and the KLA are
currently negotiating such terms and conditions as abstaining from
acts of aggression, turning over heavy weaponry, and giving up
their uniforms. On Tuesday, Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema called
on the Kosovar leaders to cooperate in disarming the KLA, adding
that the reconstruction of peace in the war-ridden Balkans was
facing many difficulties and the international community was
required to make a "very serious commitment." (Italy-Dini-KLA)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HELSINKI -- Senior U.S. and Russian officials said early
Thursday that progress has been made in their talks on settling a
dispute concerning peacekeeping in the troubled Yugoslav province
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a first round of talks with Russian
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev that ended here just before
midnight on Wednesday, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said,
"It has been a very productive day. I was pleased with the
atmosphere." Sergeyev said that "we didn't waste our time" in the
talks. He expressed agreement with Cohen that progress had been
made and that the talks would continue for reaching a formal
agreement on Russian participation in the peacekeeping force known
as KFOR. (Russia-Helsinki Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SOFIA -- Bulgaria virtually turned down Russia's request
Wednesday for permission to use a flight path or corridor to
maintain its peacekeeping forces in Kosovo, stating that Moscow
should seek permission from the KFOR commander first.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria made the decision only hours after receiving Moscow's
request for airspace to transport -- via Russian aircraft --
technical equipment, medicines and food for the Russian
peacekeepers in Kosovo, according to government spokeswoman
Stoyana Georgieva. The Bulgarian position has been coordinated
with Romania and Hungary to which a similar Russian request was
also addressed, she said. (Bulgaria-Russia-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- A Mine Action Team from Cambodia will be sent to
Kosovo to help clear mines for the safe return of Kosovo refugees,
according to a press release received Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Britain-based Mines Advisory Group (
MAG) said that a team of 16 deminers from Kompong Thom, Cambodia
will leave here Saturday for Macedonia en route to Kosovo to help
clear land for the resettlement. The team comprises men and women
as well as several amputees who are working for the MAG which does
humanitarian demining in Cambodia and around the world. (Cambodia-
Kosovo) 
</P>
</TEXT>
