<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 07:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Defense Minister Casts Doubts on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The outgoing Defense Minister
Moshe Arens has raised doubts over the U.S. military aid toward
Israel, suggesting that the annual 1.8 billion U.S.-dollar
military grants to Israel may be detrimental to the state.
</P>
<P>
Arens said this in an interview with the Jerusalem Post, which
published part of the interview Thursday and the full test of the
interview will come out Friday.
</P>
<P>
Arens said that large amount of the grants has been spent in
the United States hurtting the local industries and making it more
difficult for Israeli firms to develop quality arms.
</P>
<P>
Of the total U.S. military grants, 1.4 billion must be spent in
the United States and as a result "we are actually purchasing
things in the United States that we could be procuring here,"
Arens pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"In the long run, we are not developing certain capabilities
that we could be developing and we are not developing certain
systems that would not only give the IDF (Israel Defense Force) an
advantage in the battle-field, but could also serve as a potential
export items, such as the Arrow," he said.
</P>
<P>
Arens said he has asked the Defense Ministry to conduct a study
examining if the U.S. military aid is "in the best interest of the
Israeli industry."
</P>
<P>
"You have to remember that the U.S. aid program was designed to
aid U.S. industry. It was not just giving away presents. We are
allies of the United States and we are all for aiding
U.S. industry, but of course we have to weigh the question of
(wether to) pursue a policy that hurts Israel industry," he added.
</P>
<P>
Arens was the first Israeli government official raising
doubts about the U.S. military aid to Israel.
</P>
<P>
The United States provides 3 billion U.S. dollars as grants to
Israel annually. 1.8 billion dollars are military aids, and the
remaining part are economic grants.
</P>
<P>
Arens replaced former defense minister Yitzhak Mordechai in
January and till now he has not decided to purchase another 50
U.S. fighter jets, worthing 2.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Arrow is a anti-missile defense system Israel jointly developing
with the United States. The system succeeded in firing at
a computer-controlled target last August and would be deployed
first in Israel during the coming years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
