<HEADLINE> 17 People Feared Dead in PNG Plane Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Seventeen people, including two
Australians, are believed to have died in an aircraft crash
Thursday morning in mountainous terrain in Papua New Guinea's
(PNG) Highlands.
</P>
<P>
A twin-engine turbo-prop Bandierante aircraft operated by PNG
domestic carrier Airlink crashed about 19.3 kilometers southeast
of Goroka, in Eastern Highlands province, PNG's Office of Air
Safety Investigation said.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft, carrying 17 passengers and crew, was en route to
Goroka from Nadzab in the Morobe province, air safety investigator
Barry Awui told the Australian Associated Press (AAP).
</P>
<P>
"We suspect no survivors," Awui said.
</P>
<P>
Airlink General Manager Coliw Bubner told AAP there were two
Australians among the 15 passengers and two crew on the
Bandierante.
</P>
<P>
Awui said there had been no communication from the aircraft to
indicate that it had experienced problems.
</P>
<P>
The wreck of the aircraft was spotted by a helicopter about 11
a.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
Awui said air safety investigators hoped to travel to the crash
site Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
In February, 11 people aboard a Britten Norman Islander
aircraft operated by Airlink died when it crashed near Hoskins in
West New Britain province.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for the Australian High Commission in Port
Moresby confirmed that there were Australians aboard the crashed
aircraft but was not able to release further details. 
</P>
</TEXT>
