<HEADLINE> China Looking for Solution to Catch Elusive Winter Olympics Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- China is so eager to break its
duck at the Winter Olympic Games arenas that it will focus its
attention for the following three years upon the first Olympic
gold in the 2002 Salt Lake City Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
One year after the disappointing 18th Nagano Winter Olympics in
1998, hundreds of winter sports officials across the country were
gathering together in the Capital Stadium conference center to
find a way out.
</P>
<P>
"An Olympic gold is our premier goal in three years," said Xiao
Tian, director of the Winter Sports Management Center, at the
opening speech of the national meeting in Beijing on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We have had all kinds of gold medals in our trophy room except
the Olympic gold, which is our biggest regret in the past two
decades," Xiao said.
</P>
<P>
China won six silvers and two bronzes in the Nagano Winter
Olympics last February in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Li Jiajun led the almost overwhelming short-track team to five
silvers and one bronze in the Games, but the gold always eluded
the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
In a team boasting four to five world-class skaters, Li wrapped
up the men's overall title in the world cup series in 1998 while
Yang Yang (A) swept the women's competition last season.
</P>
<P>
Such fluctuating performances continues to perplex the sports
officials and they hope Thursday's meeting will help them find the
answer.
</P>
<P>
"No matter how much we have improved in the past years, the
elusive Olympic gold is the proof of our short-comings in training
and the lack of experiences at internationals," Xiao added.
</P>
<P>
"We're seeking for a breakthrough in the 19th Winter Games. I
believe we can make it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
