<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Stresses Acid Rain Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Acid rain remains a serious
problem to ecological environment in parts of China and a series
of urgent measures have been taken to try and control such
pollution, according to the latest environmental situation report.
</P>
<P>
The annual report released by the State Environmental
Protection Administration (SEPA) says that sulphur dioxide and
dust are the main pollutants of China's air.
</P>
<P>
However, the total volume of sulphur dioxide, smog and
industrial dust released in China last year dropped by 7.8 percent,
7.7 percent and 12.2 percent respectively, compared with 1997,
according to the report. And the treatment rate of industrial
waste gas reached 89.4 percent, up one percentage point.
</P>
<P>
The report says about 30 percent of China's total land area
suffered from acid rain as a result of smog and dust pollution
last year. The acid rain pollution in central China was alleviated
last year, while in the south, east and southwestern parts of the
country it remained the same as 1997.
</P>
<P>
Some cities in south China including Lin'an, Zhuzhou, Yiyang,
Nanchang and Changsha suffered serious acid rain pollution last
year. And Tumen in northeast China and Qingdao in east China had
no major improvements, according to the SEPA report.
</P>
<P>
In order to control acid rain, China has established acid rain
and sulphur dioxide pollution control zones covering 1.09 million
square kilometers, in which mines producing coal with sulphur
content of over three percent are banned.
</P>
<P>
A plan to further control acid rain and sulphur dioxide
pollution is being drawn up by the SEPA.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expansion of Beijing Airport Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The expansion of Beijing's
international airport has been completed after four years'
construction work and will officially open in October.
</P>
<P>
The new passenger building, covering an area of 330,000 square
meters, is three times larger than the existing one and has
transformed Capital Airport into a modern, dynamic air-passenger
hub which rivals those in developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The building boasts 51 elevators, 63 moving stairways and 26
moving footpaths. Laser scan technology will be used for luggage
checks.
</P>
<P>
Computer aided aircraft guiding systems, security equipment and
information display boards are all first rate, according to
airport sources. Test will start next month to check the
reliability of the systems.
</P>
<P>
The development is a national key project aimed at transforming
Beijing into an international metropolis. The new airport will be
able to receive 35 million passengers and 190,000 aircraft a year.
</P>
<P>
The original airport was built in the 1950s and was first
expanded in the 1970s.  
</P>
</TEXT>
