<HEADLINE> Uganda Hails S. Africa's Peaceful Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni,
who attended the inauguration of democratically-elected South
African President Thabo Mbeki in Pretoria, hailed the hand-over as
an example for other countries on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said after the ceremony that the successful transition
 consolidated democracy in the country, the New Vision paper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said he was happy about the transition, which happened to
coincide with "a generational transition from the old freedom
fighters to their children who fought with them."
</P>
<P>
An editorial in the same paper described the peaceful transfer
of power aptly representing sacrifices translated to democracy.
</P>
<P>
Change of government is often a point of crisis in most African
states. South Africa now stands out as a case to be emulated, the
editorial said.
</P>
<P>
It said that free and fair election is the key to peaceful
transfer of power.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, who assumed the office of 80-year-old Nelson Mandela,
pledged in his acceptance speech to speed the delivery of a better
life to millions of poor blacks and to minimize crimes.
</P>
<P>
Museveni is one of the 27 African heads of state and
representatives from nearly 130 countries who witnessed the grand
ceremony. 
