<HEADLINE> Lebanese President Donates Salary to Combat public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Emile Lahoud has
contributed his one-month salary to a special fund set up for
donors to help the cash-stripped government combat mounting public
debt.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud gave his 12 million Lebanese pounds (about 8,000 U.S.
dollars) in salary for May to the state coffer, the Daily Star
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
George Corm, Minister of Finance, also contributed his monthly
salary worth 8.4 million Lebanese pounds (about 5,000
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A statement by the Ministry of Finance said that the donations
were part of efforts to overcome the public debt which was
"impeding economic and social growth."
</P>
<P>
Donations to the account at the Central Bank have amounted to
nearly 110,000 dollars so far, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
A local company called Nasco Karaoglan Group donated about
50,000 dollars, which represents one percent of the salaries of
the staff.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance said it expected further donations this
month.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's public debt is currently running in excess of 18
billion dollars, more than the country's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet is discussing a five-year plan which is designed to
control the debt and reduce the huge budget deficit through the
privatization and administrative reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
