<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Energy Demand Down Slightly in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 16 (Xinhua) -- World energy demand fell by 0.
1 percent in 1998, the first fall since 1982, according to a
review report released here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"After almost a decade of relative stability in global energy
markets, 1998 saw a number of other adverse changes," said the BP
Amoco Statistical Review of World Energy 1999. BP Amoco group is
the result of a merger earlier this year between British Petroleum
and Amoco of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Energy demand from the Asian economies was hit by their
economic downturn, declining by 1.5 percent overall, with falls of
more than 6 percent seen in South Korea and Thailand, and
additional declines in both Indonesia and Japan, the review said.
</P>
<P>
In China's energy market, the review said, the year saw
exceptional change, with demand sliding by 3.2 percent --
equivalent to a 0.3 percent global drop -- despite an increasing
gross domestic product. "This may suggest structural changes in
the Chinese market toward lower energy intensity and a move away
from coal," the review said.
</P>
<P>
Demand from the former Soviet Union fell by only 0.3 percent.
But by 1998 demand from these countries had fallen 36 percent from
its 1990 peak -- a drop equivalent to 6 percent of current global
demand.
</P>
<P>
According to the BP Amoco review, the world oil markets
suffered severe disruption in 1998. Oil demand was weak, growing
by only 0.1 percent, while oil production rose by 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The world gas market was also weak, with demand up just 1.3
percent, largely due to a 3 percent fall in gas demand from the
United States.
</P>
<P>
A 6 percent fall in production of coal in China, the world's
largest producer, contributed to the 2.4 percent fall in global
production. Weak demand from China and Europe's continuing move
away from coal were reflected in the 2.1 percent fall in global
consumption.
</P>
<P>
A 7.2 percent rise in consumption of nuclear power in the U.S.
contributed to a global rise of 1.6 percent. Use of hydroelectric
power rose 1.1 percent, rising for the sixth successive year, the
review said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
