<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Telephone Company Seeks Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A Sri Lankan telephone company is
seeking a 120 million U.S. dollar loan for network expansion to
boost its depressed business, financial sources here said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Lanka Bell's Chief Executive Officer Vijay Watson said the
money was needed for their second phase of expansion. It has
invested 140 million dollars to date.
</P>
<P>
Equipment vendor Nortel of Canada, which owns a 6 percent stake
in Lanka Bell, is willing to contribute 60 million dollars for the
expansion, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
While the balance has to be sourced through debt financing from
overseas, investor sentiment remains low both due to the East
Asian financial crisis and the regulatory environment in Sri
Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Several funding agencies including the International Finance
Corporation have conducted a study on Lanka Bell but have not
taken a decision yet on committing funds.
</P>
<P>
Lanka Bell so far provides 33,000 connections while its
immediate competitor Suntel provides nearly 50,000 connections.
</P>
<P>
Both companies have been given specific targets such as
geographical reach and connections in rural areas by year 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
