<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Damon Hill Factfile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Following is the factfile of Damon
Hill, who announces retirement at the end of 1999 season:
</P>
<P>
1960: Born September 17, Hampstead, London.
</P>
<P>
1982-85: Worked as motorcycle dispatch rider to fund his racing
career.
</P>
<P>
1984: Wins in Formula Ford 1600 at Brands Hatch.
</P>
<P>
1985: Finished third in Esso Formula Ford 1600 Championship.
</P>
<P>
1986: Ninth in Formula Three Championship.
</P>
<P>
1987: Fifth in Formula Three Championship, scoring two wins.
</P>
<P>
1988: Third in Formula Three Championship, with two wins.
</P>
<P>
1990: Comes second at Brands Hatch in Formula 3000 Championship.
</P>
<P>
1991: Becomes official test driver for Williams Grand Prix team.
</P>
<P>
1992: Made Grand Prix debut for Brabham at British Grand Prix,
finishing 16th.
</P>
<P>
1993: Joined Alain Prost in Williams Grand Prix team. Won for
first time in Hungary, then added victories in Belgium and Italy.
Finished third overall in championship in first full season.
</P>
<P>
1994: Becomes unofficial number one at Williams after Ayrton
Senna died. Loses championship to Michael Schumacher by one point.
</P>
<P>
1995: Again finished second to Schumacher in championship.
</P>
<P>
1996: Wins World Championship and agrees to join Arrows team
for next season. He is awarded the OBE and named BBC sports
personality of the year.
</P>
<P>
1997: Hill scores seven points all season for Arrows and joins
Jordan in a two-year deal.
</P>
<P>
1998: Wins the Belgian Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
1999: Announces his retirement days after crashing out of the
Canadian Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
Grand Prix statistics:
</P>
<P>
Starts: 111
</P>
<P>
Wins: 22
</P>
<P>
Pole positions: 20
</P>
<P>
Total points: 359
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
