<HEADLINE> Spurs Beat Knicks in NBA Finals Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- San Antonio Spurs beat New York
Knicks 89-77 in the opening game of the National Basketball
Association Finals in San Antonio, Texas, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
San Antonio's Tim Duncan scored 33 points and grabbed 16
rebounds while teammate David Robinson contributed 13 points plus
9 rebounds in their 11th consecutive playoff win, which tied the
NBA record.
</P>
<P>
New York Knicks' Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell finished
with 19 points apiece. The Eastern Conference winner was without
veteran center Patrick Ewing due to a season-ending injury earlier
in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
The Spurs surged to lead at half time 45-37 and led by as many
as 15 points in the final period.
</P>
<P>
San Antonio, which had the best regular-season record in the
league, shot 48 percent while holding New York to 38 percent from
the floor.
</P>
<P>
Game 2 of the best-of-seven series is on Friday, again at San
Antonio's Alamodome, before the Finals shift to New York. 
</P>
