<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Allow Local Language Subtitling of Foreign Videos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar will allow captioning of
Myanmar subtitles or dubbing in Myanmar language of imported
foreign feature videos, The New Light of Myanmar Thursday quoted
the Ministry of Information as saying.
</P>
<P>
The undertakings will be allowed if the copy-right owner
permits, according to the Myanmar Motion Picture Enterprise of the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
The foreign videos and tapes must have already been approved
for public and family show, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, there have been foreign feature films telecast
by two Myanmar state-run television stations with Myanmar
subtitles on them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, production of local video films grows rapidly
because of high demand.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, 547 local video films were
produced in 1998, much more than motion pictures which were only
15.
</P>
<P>
In order to properly control and manage the video industry, the
ministry revised last December some rules under the existing 1996
Television and Video Law, revoking some television and video
procedures.
</P>
<P>
The Video Censor Board was also established to check films and
videos in accordance with concerned policies, rules and standards
to make sure they are suitable to be shown to the public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Boost Exports with New Moves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Thai ministers from finance,
industry, agriculture, commerce and related government agencies
will gather together and discuss the way to keep exports levels as
high as possible in the second half of this year, The Nation said
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The second so-called "Export Summit" will be organized by the
Export Development Committee in late July, which aimed at closely
monitoring progress of exports, the newspaper quoted Deputy Prime
Minister and Commerce Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government holds the summit to bolster exports as it is
worried that exports could plunge during the rest of the year,
dragging the economy with it, Supachai said.
</P>
<P>
In March, the government held its first summit meeting,
implementing many export-friendly measures, such as cash flow
supports and import tariff exemptions.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Thailand's exports appeared to have recovered from
declines in three consecutive months in 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics of the Customs Department, the
country's export value in revenue in U.S. dollar terms in April
grew 4.7 percent to 4.53 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Supachai predicted Wednesday that the exports in May will
increase by least 6 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said he believed that Thailand's exports can grow by 4
percent to 56.6 billion dollars throughout the year as targeted.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Thailand's exports shrank 9 percent, when the total
gross domestic product contracted 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said after monitoring for several months the movements
of 13 important export products such as integrated circuits,
vehicles, plastic products, computers, values were found to have
increased sharply.
</P>
<P>
Those products accounted for 68 percent of Thailand's total
exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
