<HEADLINE> Experts Discuss Protection on Migrant Women's Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Legal experts and women's
federation workers are calling for more specific laws and special
organizations to guarantee adequate care for the growing number of
migrant women workers.
</P>
<P>
They made the proposal in Beijing Wednesday during the first
day of a three-day national symposium organized by China Women's
News for examining ways of protecting migrant women worker's
rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
Participants from 20 provinces are discussing issues relating
to migrant women workers' rights and interests, their education
levels, training and marriages.
</P>
<P>
The term "migrant women workers" usually refers to rural girls
who move to cities to find work. They are commonly employed as
housekeepers, waitresses or by toy or textile factories.
</P>
<P>
"These women are vulnerable to infringements upon their rights
and interests, due to their low education levels and insufficient
awareness of their rights," said Zhou Wanling, an official with
the Legal Consultancy Division of the All-China Federation of
Trade Unions.
</P>
<P>
They are likely, due to the same reason, to find themselves in
unfavorable positions with their employers.
</P>
<P>
"To help these women protect themselves, lawyers and women's
federation workers should teach them about their rights, and how
they can effectively safeguard these rights,' Miao Zhennan, vice-
director of the Women Studies Institute under the Sichuan
Federation of Women, said, quoted by today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Training courses should be offered regularly to migrant women
workers, she added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
