<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet's State Firms Making Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- While state-owned enterprises in
most parts of China are suffering deficits, their counterparts in
the Tibet Autonomous Region are beginning to become profitable as
a whole.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, local government has helped state companies
deal with management problems, backward technology and lack of
information, and has, meanwhile, issued favorable policies to help
them improve operations.
</P>
<P>
So far, five Tibet-headquartered state firms have been listed,
while many other companies have experienced changes and reforms of
various types, including rebuilding of managerial mechanism and
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the state sector generated 17 million yuan worth of
profits as a whole, with only 10 percent of state-owned
enterprises still in the red.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, a number of locally produced name-brand products sell
well throughout the country, such as Zhufeng motorcycles and
Qizheng Tibetan medicine.
</P>
<P>
Some state companies in Tibet have cooperated with inland firms.
The Lhasa Brewery was once trapped in a loss of 27 million yuan,
but its fate was changed in 1995, when a company from neighboring
Sichuan Province took over part of its stocks by investing 36
million yuan in the brewery.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the brewery, the largest in the autonomous region,
achieved a sales income of more than 50 million yuan, with its
profits and taxes exceeding 10 million yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
