<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Megawati Gets Military, Party Support for Presidential Candidacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Armed Forces (TNI) and
the National Mandate Party (PAN) Wednesday both expressed their
support for Megawati Soekarnoputri, chairwoman of the Indonesian
Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P) which continued its lead in
the vote count of the June 7 elections, to be the next president.
</P>
<P>
Controversy has arisen over the gender of the next president,
which the PDI-P claims is a maneuver to bar the party's chairwoman
from contesting the presidential race. The Muslim-based United
Development Party (PPP) has recommended that only a male Muslim
candidate be eligible for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
TNI Chief of Territorial Affairs Lt. Gen. Susilo Bambang
Yudhoyono reiterated that the TNI was hoping that the best citizen
in the state, "either a man or a woman," would be elected
president.
</P>
<P>
TNI high command has not issued any order to its faction in the
People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) to throw its support behind
any particular presidential candidate, national newspapers
Thursday quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under Indonesia's constitution, it is the MPR that is empowered
to choose the president. The MPR is scheduled to meet in November.
</P>
<P>
The MPR, the country's supreme legislative body, will comprise
the House of Representatives (DPR) members plus 200 appointed
regional and interest groups' representatives. The House itself
will have 500 members, 462 of whom will come from the 48 political
parties that contested the June 7 general election. The remaining
38 members will be military and policemen appointed by the TNI
leadership.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, TNI deputy spokesman Brig. Gen. Sudrajat
said, "We do not discriminate between men and women in terms of
leadership, as long as the people agree to elect her and as long
as the election is democratic, transparent, free and fair."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the military would use its political weight to
push democracy and protect the unity of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, PAN General Chairman Amien Rais Rais said that he
had buried his dreams of becoming president and implied that the
president's gender was not of concern to PAN.
</P>
<P>
"According to the Holy Qur'an, which I believe as absolutely
right because it was revealed from the Almighty, both men and
women are on an equal footing," Rais said.
</P>
<P>
Enjoying a lion's share of votes in provisional tallies, the
PDI-P is widely expected to maintain its lead until the completion
of the vote counting process and the formal declaration of the
polls.
</P>
<P>
As of Thursday morning, according to the General Elections
Commission (KPU), the PDI-P was leading with 18 million votes,
followed by the National Awakening Party (PKB) with 9.2 million
votes, ruling Golkar Party with 8 million, PPP with 4.6 million
and PAN with 3.2 million.
</P>
<P>
According to unofficial results from the Joint Operation Media
Center which had counted over 70 million votes, the PDI-P was also
on top, but Golkar was in second place, trailed by PKB, PPP and
PAN.
</P>
<P>
General Chairman of Golkar Akbar Tanjung Wednesday admitted
that there appeared to be little chance that his party would catch
up with the PDI-P in the collection of votes.
</P>
<P>
He, however, said that second place was still respectable.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the final results of the election will be
issued by the KPU on June 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
