<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's GDP Grows By 2.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's gross domestic product
(GDP) in real terms grew by 2.7 percent during the first quarter
of this year compared to 5.7 percent in the corresponding period
of 1998, according to the latest figures issued by the Central
Bank.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of 1999, production increased by 3.3
percent in manufacturing, 5 percent in construction, 2.9 percent
in services and 0.8 percent in agriculture, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The services sector contributed 56 percent to the overall GDP
growth while the manufacturing sector contributed 18 percent, the
construction sector 14 percent and the agriculture and fishing
sector 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Due to a decline in foreign demand as a result of the depressed
world economic situation, growth in factory industry was lower
than last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the food, beverages and tobacco industries grew by 3.2
percent supported by a rise in domestic demand. The
export-oriented apparel industry grew by 4.2 percent due to
greater diversification.
</P>
<P>
The output of chemical products, rubber goods and petroleum
declined by 2.1 percent while tea, rubber and coconut kernel
products rose by 10.5 percent, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The construction sector grew by 5 percent and the
communications sector expanded by 49 percent with 73,641 new
telephones being provided.
</P>
<P>
The volume of containerized cargo handled declined by 2.6
percent while aviation services expanded by 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
The electricity, gas and water sector grew by 8 percent while
wholesale and retail trade showed a negative growth of 2.6 percent
as a result of a decline in import and slower export and domestic
trade, the bank added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
