<HEADLINE> Myanmar Bank Opens Branch to Support Industrial Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Innwa Bank Ltd., a financial
institution of the semi-official Myanmar Economic Corporation, has
opened a branch in Mandalay, the country's second largest city in
the north, to provide financial backing to the local industrial
zone, one of the 18 being established in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Mandalay branch, which was inaugurated on Wednesday, is
aimed at boosting industrial productivity on a commercial scale,
and ensuring safety for investment and property of local and
foreign companies and rapid accumulation and circulation of money
for global investors and local and foreign bank branches, said
Myanmar Deputy Prime Minister Lieutenant-General Tin Hla at the
inaugural ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The Innwa Bank was established with a special purpose to serve
as a strong financial center for the country's industrial zones,
industries of the cooperative and private sectors, export
enterprises and farming industries.
</P>
<P>
The Innwa Bank has earlier opened one branch each in Yangon,
Taunggyi and Mongshu, and is planning to open more in other states
and divisions.
</P>
<P>
Apart from providing local services, the bank will also act as
a correspondent bank of international banks with strong financial
power.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, there are 17 private banks
and three state-owned banks providing commercial banking services
in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, nearly 60 private bank branches had been
opened throughout the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
