<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Countries Discuss Social Impact of Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Delegates from Asian economies and
international organizations gathered here Thursday to assess the
social impact of the region's two-year-old financial crisis and
find ways to strengthen social protection systems in the region.
</P>
<P>
Country reports on six Asian countries -- Indonesia, South
Korea, Laos, Malaysia, the Philippines and Thailand -- will be
presented during the two-day conference.
</P>
<P>
The meeting aims to assist in devising policy responses to the
social crisis and identifying measures that would improve social
protection systems in the longer term, according to the Asian
Development Bank (ADB), organizer of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Opening the meeting Thursday morning, ADB President Tadao Chino
said that the Asian crisis appears to be bottoming out and the
crisis-hit economies are starting to show signs of revival.
</P>
<P>
"Full recovery is likely to take longer, however," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the crisis is impacting the social sectors via
labor markets, prices, assets, credit and government budget.
</P>
<P>
"Unemployment represents the most direct impact of the crisis
on human well-being. At the same time, high inflation ignited by
the currency depreciation has eroded real incomes," Chino said.
</P>
<P>
Besides these immediate costs, he said, the crisis has
potentially longer social consequences.
</P>
<P>
But the inadequacy of social safety nets is common in
developing Asia and even worse in the poorer economies of the
region, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Poverty reduction, indeed, continues to be the major challenge
to the region, despite significant improvements made possible by
dynamic economic growth in many of the region's countries over two
decades or so," the ADB president said.
</P>
<P>
He called on Asian economies to redouble efforts to reduce
poverty and improve social protection systems so that the poor
groups can better weather social shocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Number 10 on List of Global Coal Producers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia has been placed as the
10th biggest coal producer in the world with a production of 57
million tons which is expected to increase to 81 million tons in
the year 2000 and 102 million tons in 2003.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has a big chance to grab more opportunities in the
international market which is growing at 10 percent a year, chief
executive of London-based World Coal Institute Ron Knapp said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"As one of the major suppliers of steam coal, Indonesia has the
potential markets in Japan, South Korea, Germany, the Netherlands,
Denmark and the United Kingdom with total demand recorded at 321
million tons last year," he said.
</P>
<P>
In steam coal exports, Indonesia ranks as the fourth biggest
exporter after the United States, South Africa and Australia.
</P>
<P>
According to Knapp, the market for thermal coal is also big
with demand expected to reach 345 million tons in 2000 in Japan,
other Asian countries and Europe.
</P>
<P>
"However, Indonesia has tough competitors from new entries,
namely Colombia and Venezuela," The Indonesian Observer Thursday
quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The production of Colombian coal reached 32.7 million tons in
1997 and is expected to increase to 43 million tons in 2000 and 51
million tons in 2003, while Venezuela's production reached 5.3
million tons in 1997 with expectation to increase to 11 million
tons in 2000 and 22 million tons in 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
