<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Guangdong Spurs Spending to Ensure Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Banks in this southern Chinese
province of Guangdong have been offering loans to individual
consumers for education, travel, interior remodeling of housing
and purchase of major durable consumer commodities since the
beginning of this month.
</P>
<P>
In Guangzhou, the provincial capital, a dozen major general
merchandise stores have signed agreements with local banks to
provide customers with loans to buy major consumer commodities.
</P>
<P>
An Xuesong, who recently signed an agreement with the Bank of
China (BOC) Guangdong Branch to obtain a loan for supporting his
MBA studies at Jinan University, said: "the loan makes it possible
for me to concentrate on study, and I can easily repay the loan
after I go to work."
</P>
<P>
Previously, An had to rely on aids from relatives and part-time
job pay for tuition fees and living expenditure.
</P>
<P>
Banks in the southern Chinese province also offer loans to
individuals for purchase of apartments and cars. In the first
quarter of the year, the BOC Guangdong Branch provided mortgage
loans worth 400 million yuan for housing and issued another 12
million yuan worth of loans for car purchase.
</P>
<P>
The measures demonstrate the provincial government's
determination to accelerate local economic development by spurring
individual consumption, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong is set to achieve an economic growth rate of nine
percent this year. It reported a ten-percent growth last year in
spite of the adverse impact of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
