<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Hosts International Meteorological Seminar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Some 300 meteorologists around the
world attending a seminar in Beijing seek to put forward new
climate-changing predicting models with the help of worldwide
experiments.
</P>
<P>
The four-day seminar, composed of the Third International
Scientific Conference on Global Energy and the Water Cycle (GEWEX)
and the Fourth Study Conference on GEWEX Asian Monsoon Experiment
(GAME), is the first and largest of its kind ever held in Asia,
said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
GEWEX began in 1989 and is the largest climate and
environmental project in the World Weather Research Program, whose
major task is to observe, learn and simulate the exchange and
cycles of water vapor from the atmosphere, the land and oceans and
their related heat energies.
</P>
<P>
The experiments are to play an important role in raising
predictability of the global precipitation and evaporation, and
accurately evaluating radiation processes within the atmosphere
and the susceptibility of climate changes caused by clouds, the
report quoted the experts as saying.
</P>
<P>
The experiments are expected to help people make sensible
utilization of the globe's shrinking water resources and deal with
worsening water pollution resulted from various environmental
problems in the world today.
</P>
<P>
China has, since 1998, sponsored four large-scale
meteorological experiments, the largest in China's meteorological
history, with the participation of some 6,000 technicians and 600
meteorologists, said officials with the China Meteorological
Administration.
</P>
<P>
Data observed through the experiments in the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau, the South China Sea, the Huaihe River and the Taiwan
Straits have push forward studies of monsoons in Asia and East
Asia and the disastrous weather in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
