<HEADLINE> Central China City Becoming Overseas Investment Destination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Wuhan, capital of Hubei Province in
central China, has become home to 3,458 overseas-financed
businesses, with overseas investment accounting for a quarter of
its fixed assets.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of May, these overseas-backed
enterprises had paid in 2.9 billion U.S. dollars of investment.
They will invest a total of 4.7 billion dollars according to
contracts.
</P>
<P>
Out of the world's 500 top companies, 29 have made investments
in Wuhan, which sits at the middle reaches of the Yangtze River,
the country's longest, while 45 others have set up business
offices and another 63 have sent missions to make inspections in
the city.
</P>
<P>
Many of the overseas investors have been increasing their
investments in the central China city since the start of the year,
according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
At a recent forum, Luo Qingquan, the city's Party chief, told
resident representatives of multinationals that the city would
concentrate on opening up markets in Europe, the United States and
Japan, and stepping up cooperation with Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He said his city would soon work out a list of major projects
for overseas investment, and would keep improving investment
environment and drafting preferential policies to attract more
multinationals to Wuhan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
