<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relics From Three Gorges Area on Display </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The city of Chongqing in
southwest China is displaying relics unearthed in the Three Gorges
area on the middle reaches of the Yangtze River, where China's
largest water control project is being built.
</P>
<P>
On show are 249 valuable relics spanning millions of years from
the Old Stone Age, along with photos, graphics, and documents.
</P>
<P>
Since 1997, Chinese archeologists have been working hard to
excavate the area before it is inundated when the dam project is
completed.
</P>
<P>
There are 1,238 places of cultural relics in the Three Gorges
area, 845 of which are in Chongqing. In the past two years, 31
excavation teams have gone to the area and have dug up nearly 10,
000 relics in 45 sites.  
</P>
</TEXT>
