<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State-Owned Enterprises in NE China Concentrating on Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- State-owned enterprises in
Liaoning Province, northeast China, are now increasingly
separating services like schools and hospitals from themselves in
a bid to sharp their competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
The most important 60 provincial enterprises have turned 398
affiliated schools, hospitals, and canteens over to local
governments or made them independent units.
</P>
<P>
There were some 22 firms and social service departments that
were separated last year from the Benxi Iron and Steel Company,
one of the largest state-owned enterprises in the province.
</P>
<P>
Most state-owned enterprises in China used to have their own
schools, hospitals, kindergartens, and canteens, which added a
heavy financial burden.
</P>
<P>
In the city of Dalian, the government has accepted 25 schools
from 14 state-owned enterprises and has written preferential tax
and land utilization policies for state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Provincial officials say that they plan to expand the move to 2,
660 state-owned companies within the next two years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
