<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil's Coffee Exports Recover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's coffee exports
have increased sharply, allowing it to resume its traditional
position as the world's largest coffee bean supplier.
</P>
<P>
For the period of July 1998 to June 1999, the South American
country exported 19.59 million sacks of coffee (60 kilos per sack),
the greatest amount in the last eight years, for 2.3 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Brazil produced 35 million sacks of coffee this year, the
highest amount in the last 11 years and almost a third of the
world's total.
</P>
<P>
However, during the past few years, Brazil had been overtaken
by their main rivals, Colombia and the Central American countries,
Brazilian exporters were quoted as saying by Wednesday's "
Mercantile Gazette."
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Brazil, the world's largest producer and
exporter of coffee, has produced 27 percent of the coffee being
offered on the international markets this year, up from 21 percent
over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The recovery is due to the fact that Brazil is the top-seller
of coffee in the United States, which is the world's largest
market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
