<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar-Japan Bilateral Trade Slightly Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar-Japan bilateral trade
reached 44.71 million U.S. dollars in the first two months of this
year, slightly increasing by 2.35 percent over the 43.68 million
dollars registered in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest figures published by Myanmar's Central
Statistical Organization, Myanmar's import from Japan was 36.55
million dollars during the two-month period, dropping by 2.76
million dollars from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
However, Myanmar's export to Japan during the period increased
to 8.16 million dollars from 4.37 million dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The figures also show that the balance of trade in the period
was considerably in favor of Japan since Japan's export to
Myanmar accounted for a high percentage of 81.7 of the total
bilateral trade, while its import from Myanmar represented just a
percentage of 18.3.
</P>
<P>
Japan is one of Myanmar's major trading partners in Asia. Japan
mainly exports to Myanmar machinery, chemical materials, rubber
manufactures and motor vehicles, while importing from it
agricultural, forest and marine products.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, in 1998, Japan's export to
Myanmar amounted to 346.8 million dollars, while its import from
Myanmar was only 42.69 million dollars, a huge trade deficit
occurring in Myanmar's balance of trade with Japan.
</P>
<P>
To reduce the trade deficit, Myanmar is trying to restrict its
import from Japan and stepping up exploration of unexploited
export sectors of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
