<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Scientists Discover Anti-AIDS Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Australian National University
researchers have discovered a drug which, in laboratory testing,
has been shown to be able to stop AIDS virus in its tracks, the
Canberra Times said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Researchers were quoted as saying that independent laboratory
tests, conducted on mammalian cells in test tubes, have shown that
the drug stopped the AIDS virus replicating.
</P>
<P>
Parallel work was also being done on viral fevers, such as
dengue, Ross River and Barnah Forest fevers, and there were also
applications for the new drug in helping stroke and heart-attack
sufferers, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The work focused on ion channels, proteins that sit on a cell
membrane and provide pathways for the transmission of charged
particles and viruses into the cell, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The drug, developed with technology which the researchers have
been working on for 15 years, has been shown to be able to "block"
a virus into the cell, it said.
</P>
<P>
Professor Peter Gage, one of the researchers, said that "by
finding the precise location and form of a disorder at the
molecular level, it is possible to identify or design a drug to
lock on to the site and interact with ion flow to stop the
pathological condition."
</P>
<P>
"The benefit of this targeted approach is that the effect of
the disorder is arrested, and there are no, or minimal, side
effects," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico's Tremor Death Toll Rises to 20 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from an
earthquake that hit south-central Mexico rose to 20 Wednesday,
with some 600 people left homeless and 4,000 displaced, an
official report said.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake, measuring 6.7 on the Richter scale and lasting
about 40 seconds on Tuesday mid-afternoon, was the strongest on
record over the last 14 years in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter was in Huajuapan de Leon, the state of Puebla,
about 100 kilometers southeast of the capital. The seismic wave
was felt in the states of Chiapas, Guerrero, Mexico, Michoacan,
Morelos, Tlaxcala and Veracruz.
</P>
<P>
The report said 15 people were killed in Puebla, which
sustained the worst damage, two in Mexico City, two in Veracruz
and one in Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
Some 80 buildings were damaged and at least 125 homes were
affected in Puebla, a colonial city known for its facades of hand-
painted ceramic tiles of the 17th century and declared by the U.N.
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization as a place of "
humanity heritage."
</P>
<P>
President Ernesto Zedillo ordered care for the victims
immediately after the quake and, accompanied by General in command
of the area Enrique Cervantes, made a quick tour of the affected
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
