<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress Made in U.S.-Russia Talks on Peacekeeping in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Senior U.S. and Russian officials
said early Thursday that progress has been made in their talks on
settling a dispute concerning peacekeeping in the troubled
Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a first round of talks with Russian
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev that ended here just before
midnight on Wednesday, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said,
"It has been a very productive day. I was pleased with the
atmosphere."
</P>
<P>
"We had a long, productive afternoon and evening, but we have
more to go," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We've had some agreements in some areas, but until the entire
package as such is resolved, there can be no agreement," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking to reporters, Sergeyev said that "we didn't waste
our time" in the talks. He expressed agreement with Cohen that
progress had been made and that the talks would continue for
reaching a formal agreement on Russian participation in the
peacekeeping force known as KFOR.
</P>
<P>
In remarks released by Russia's Itar-Tass news agency, Sergeyev
said, "We have reached an agreement on the structure of command of
the peacekeeping operation with the participation of the Russian
military contingent."
</P>
<P>
He also cautioned that all of the issues concerned are very
complex and "we cannot resolve them just right away."
</P>
<P>
Neither side would reveal further details of the talks or
agreement.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Russian Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov were also to hold talks on the issue in
Helsinki on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Russia and the U.S.-led NATO have been in a dispute over Russia
's role in Kosovo peacekeeping after the deployment of 200 Russian
troops to Kosovo on Saturday where they took control of Pristina
airport and were in a standoff with NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
The crux of the dispute is NATO's demand that all countries
participating in Kosovo peacekeeping operate under a unified
command led by NATO. Russia is opposed to such a demand.
</P>
<P>
Russia demands that it play an independent role in the
peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
One possible compromise option might be to include a senior
Russian officer in the KFOR command structure, Russian media
reports said.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, U.S. officials have also said NATO is trying to
create a "zone of responsibility" for Russian peacekeepers that
would perhaps be part of the five NATO sectors.
</P>
<P>
Before the talks started, both the U.S. and Russia expressed
confidence that an agreement could be reached on a compromise
under which Russian troops would serve in the 50,000-member KFOR.
</P>
<P>
NATO has set up five military sectors in Kosovo under U.S.,
British, French, German and Italian control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
