<HEADLINE> China Invests Heavily in Southwestern Railways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- China is pouring huge amount of
money into railway projects in the southwest in a bid to boost
local development by easing the traffic bottleneck in this
mountainous region densely populated by ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
During the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000), China plans
to invest 250 billion yuan in railway construction projects, with
27 percent, or 68 billion yuan, of the total going to the
southwest.
</P>
<P>
The huge investment is aimed to improve the southwestern
railway network and its links with other parts of the country,
according to a senior official of the Ministry of Railways.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, a number of railway projects have been completed in
southwest China, including the first one in the region that leads
to the sea.
</P>
<P>
In the coming few years, 10 other projects are going to be
built to link up major cities in the region.
</P>
<P>
The long-awaited railways to Tibet have once again drawn people
's attention recently, said the official, adding that one of the
routes is expected to start from Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
Local experts are also talking about laying a Pan-Asian railway
network to link southwest China with Southeast Asia nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
