<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia's Coffee Production Predicted to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's coffee
production in 1999-2000 is expected to drop after the main crop
areas were hit by heavy rains at the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian coffee harvest is going through one of its worst
moments, due to the heavy rains caused by "La Nina" towards the
end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The downpours caused a 20.9 percent fall in the production,
cutting the harvest to 3.5 million sacks in the first five months
of this year, compared with 4.4 million in the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
According to the director of FEDECAFE, the national federation
of coffee growers, the crisis could worsen during the second half
of this year and at the beginning of 2000.
</P>
<P>
The authorities predict that coffee production in the 1998-1999
period will be 11 million sacks, lower than their original
prediction of 12.5 million sacks and the 1997-1998 production of
12.1 million.
</P>
<P>
As the second largest coffee supplier in the world after Brazil,
Colombia exports around two billion U.S. dollars worth of coffee
on an annual basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
