<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Turns Down Russian Request for Air Corridor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria virtually turned down
Russia's request Wednesday for permission to use a flight path or
corridor to maintain its peacekeeping forces in Kosovo, stating
that Moscow should seek permission from the KFOR commander first.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria made the decision only hours after receiving Moscow's
request for airspace to transport -- via Russian aircraft --
technical equipment, medicines and food for the Russian
peacekeepers in Kosovo, according to government spokeswoman
Stoyana Georgieva.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian position has been coordinated with Romania and
Hungary to which a similar Russian request was also addressed, she
said.
</P>
<P>
"Any entry of persons or equipment into Kosovo should occur
only with the permission of KFOR (U.N. peacekeeping forces in
Kosovo) Commander General Michael Jackson," Georgieva said.
</P>
<P>
She also denied Russian reports which quoted Russia's Balkans
envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin as saying that "the question of flights
of Russian military aircraft over Bulgaria has been settled. It is
expected that corridors will (also) be provided by Hungary and
Romania."
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman added that "there is no change in the Bulgarian
position." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
