<HEADLINE> U.S. House Rejects Ban on Youth Access to Materials on Sex, Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives voted Wednesday 282-146 to reject proposed curbs
on youth access to explicit sexual or violent material in video
games, movies and other art and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
Both Republican and Democratic lawmakers expressed concern that
the proposed restrictions violated the Constitution's free speech
guarantee.
</P>
<P>
Republican lawmaker Henry Hyde, who proposed the curbs on
sexual and violent material for minors, said they were designed to
be "the slow flood of toxic waste into our kids' minds."
</P>
<P>
"Parents need our help. Let's stand with them. Nothing we do
in this life is more important than how we raise our children,"
said Henry, Chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, but his
proposal was not responded positively by most lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
At the same time the house voted 249-181 to toughen law
enforcement against juvenile offenders.
</P>
<P>
The law enforcement measures include a requirement that all U.S.
Attorneys designate prosecutors to specialize in firearms cases so
that more such cases can be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
Stricter penalties are also required for numerous crimes,
including illegal possession of a gun with the intent to take it
into a school zone.
</P>
<P>
The provision will authorize prosecutors, rather than judges,
to have discretion to charge a juvenile as an adult. 
</P>
</TEXT>
