<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Following are highlights of today'
s major Beijing-based newspapers.
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The People's Daily, China's leading newspaper, continues its
campaign to highlight the "Three Emphases" on education within the
Communist Party of China by publishing its 11th commentary on the
topic on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The commentary, entitled "Rectification is the Kernel," says
rectification and correction must be carried out in the whole
process of the "Three Emphases" on education program, so that the
people could see and feel the positive changes and progress
brought about by the campaign.
</P>
<P>
-- China has decided to push forward education designed to
improve the quality of students which encourage originality in
them and improve their practical abilities. The decision was
announced earlier this week by the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) and the State Council.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji met with Bulgarian Foreign
Minister Nadezhda Mikhailova in Beijing yesterday. Zhu exchanged
views with the minister on bilateral ties and issues of common
concern.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Lanqing, a member of the Standing Committee of the
Political Bureau of the Central Committee of the Communist Party
of China, attended the 1999 National University Students Art
Festival in Beijing yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- Guangming Daily, a leading national newspaper, celebrated
the 50th anniversary of its founding yesterday in Beijing. Party
and state leaders Jiang Zemin, Li Peng, Zhu Rongji and Li Ruihuan
wrote inscription for or sent congratulations to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
-- China is now establishing a social security network
including endowment insurance, medicare and unemployment insurance
to provide cover for the employees of enterprises and retired
workers.
</P>
<P>
A recent report, jointly issued by the Ministry of Labor and
Social Security and the National Bureau of Statistics, showed that
over 80 percent of employees and 98 percent of retired workers in
China have joined a relevant social security network.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Dayang No 1, a Chinese ship for exploring seabed resources,
yesterday began another pioneering voyage to a zone of the Pacific
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
-- China will gradually increase education funding, which will
eventually be four percent of the country's gross domestic product,
according to a decision issued by the Chinese Communist Party
Central Committee and the State Council.
</P>
<P>
-- A national credit guarantee system to be established soon is
expected to relieve the capital crunch for most small and medium-
sized enterprises. 
</P>
