<HEADLINE> Canada, Austria Call for Stability Plan for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien and his Austrian counterpart Viktor Klima underlined here
Wednesday the necessity of working out a stability plan to achieve
a lasting peace in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a joint press conference after their talks, Chretien
stated that Canada, as a NATO member, would participate in the
international peacekeeping mission in the Yugoslav province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
However, he said he had not yet known what the Canadian troops'
tasks will be and where the expenses needed for the mission will
come from.
</P>
<P>
Austrian Prime Minister Klima said on the occasion that the
European Union (EU) would work with NATO in taking measures to
support the reconstruction and ensure peace in the Balkans within
the framework of the proposed stability plan.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting with Chretien, Klima reportedly reiterated
his country's neutrality in dealing with international issues.
</P>
<P>
Chretien arrived earlier Wednesday for a two-day working visit
to Austria. He is expected to meet with Austrian President Thomas
Klestil and other senior Austrian officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
