<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Seeds Eliminated in Eastbourne </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Top seeds Monica Seles and Arantxa
Sanchez Vicario were crashed out of the Eastbourne International
Challenge women's tennis tournament on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Seles, first seed, lost to Anne Kremer of Luxembourg 6-4, 6-4
while second seeded Spaniard Sanchez Vicario was beaten by 20-year-
old French player Nathalie Dechy 7-5, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
The defeats are major setbacks for the world numbers four and
seven as they prepare for the grasscourt Grand Slam event in five
days' time.
</P>
<P>
Seles, Eastbourne champion in 1996, and Sanchez Vicario, a
finalist here in each of her last three appearances, both expected
to do well.
</P>
<P>
But neither produced the form they are capable of as the
youngsters grasped their opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"Well, at least it's better that it happened here and not at
Wimbledon," Sanchez Vicario said afterwards.
</P>
<P>
"Every time I got an opportunity I just missed it. She attacked
better than me, she played better than me and she deserved to win.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously I would have liked to have stayed in the tournament
a little longer to get good match practice but now I am going to
go to London tomorrow and start practicing there."
</P>
<P>
Seles, like Sanchez Vicario, received a bye in the first round
and so was playing for the first time on grass this year.
</P>
<P>
"I was making far too many errors but it is just very hard to
understand what happened today," she said.
</P>
<P>
"It's not a tragedy but I must try and learn from what happened.
I've had a couple of matches this year where my game has just
collapsed, and that was the case out there."
</P>
<P>
The American former world number one's game did collapse on
Devonshire Park's centre court as Kremer moved her from side to
side.
</P>
<P>
The 40th-ranked Kremer, making her first appearance in the main
draw, began to produce the sort of angles her more famous opponent
is known for and Seles simply sprayed balls long and wide.
</P>
<P>
It is a result that Kremer will not forget. "She was my
favourite player growing up," the 23-year-old beamed afterwards.
</P>
<P>
"I always loved her fast game so it is so good to go out and
beat her playing like that."
</P>
<P>
Third seed and 1998 Wimbledon finalist Nathalie Tauziat showed
the top two how it should be done by dismissing Austria's Sylvia
Plischke 6-3, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Fourth seed Amanda Coetzer also got her campaign off to a solid
start. The South African beat qualifier Elena Tatarkova
comfortably 6-3, 6-4. She meets compatriot Mariaan De Swardt in
the quarters after De Swardt dismissed seventh seed Irina Spirlea
6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Sixth seed Natasha Zvereva followed up Tuesday's victory over
Tara Snyder by beating 17-year-old Mirjana Lucic 7-5, 6-1. She
meets Kremer in the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
Fifth seed Anna Kournikova eased past American Lisa Raymond
after a tricky start in their second round match.
</P>
<P>
Raymond forced Kournikova to a tiebreak in the opening set
which the young Russian won 7-4 before taking control and winning
the second set 6-4, earning a quarter-final against Dechy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
