<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Enhance Computer Network Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- China's leading industrial and
commercial city of Shanghai will slice off 10 to 15 percent of its
computer network development funds for network security purposes,
according to Deputy Mayor Chen Liangyu.
</P>
<P>
Chen said his city will replace all imported network security
products with homemade ones to ensure maximum safety.
</P>
<P>
Measures will be taken to tighten control of the quality of
products that are used to protect the networks from intruders,
Chen said.
</P>
<P>
A municipal information security testing evaluation and
certification center is set to be established soon to ensure
thorough testing on the quality and performance of such products.
</P>
<P>
As information networks are present in nearly all segments of
society, Chen stressed, it is of vital importance to guarantee the
security of the networks.
</P>
<P>
To date, 86 percent of Shanghai's information networks have had
security products mounted, but a recent survey showed a lack of
security knowledge among network professionals, with less than two
percent of them knowing how to protect their networks from
intruders. Most of the security products are imported.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
