<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Islamabad Hopes Diplomacy to Prevail Over War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 17 (Xinhua) -- As clouds of a widening armed
conflict between Pakistan and India following the recent flare-up
in the disputed Kashmir area hover over the South Asian horizon,
Islamabad still hopes diplomacy to prevail over war.
</P>
<P>
Despite the latest conflict, Pakistan still hopes that the
tension along the Line of Control (LoC), which has lasted for
more than one and a half month, would be de-escalated by
diplomatic means.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in his telephone conversation with
his Indian counterpart Atal Bihari Vajpayee last Sunday reiterated
Pakistan's desire to defuse the current tension on LoC.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, who had earlier made a telephone call to Vajpayee on
May 28, expressed his hope that India would join Pakistan in
devising mutually acceptable approaches to preserve peace and
prevent the South Asian region from descending into chaos and
conflagration.
</P>
<P>
"If diplomacy fails, war is inevitable. But we will persist
with our diplomatic efforts because in this world the costs of
failure of diplomacy were huge and unbearable," Foreign Office
spokesman Tariq Altaf said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz and his Indian
counterpart Jaswant Singh in their meeting held last weekend in
New Delhi agreed to disagree on how to de-escalate the situation
following India's air strikes to flush out Kashmiri militants from
the strategic heights of Kashmir's Kargil sector.
</P>
<P>
India insisted that Pakistan withdraw the alleged Muslim
infiltrators from Kargil heights to pave the way for further
talks. But Pakistan denied the charges and urged India to halt
air raids and artillery duels to create a congenial atmosphere for
more talks.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said that Pakistan has proposed international
monitoring of the 720-kilometer-long LoC, which divides Kashmir
between the two South Asian rivals, to verify the allegations of
infiltration.
</P>
<P>
"We want a great role of UNMOGIP (United Nations Military
Observer Group for India and Pakistan) which should be allowed to
monitor and report any violations (of LoC) from any side," said
Shraf Jehangir Qazi, Pakistan's ambassador to India, who was also
a member of Aziz's negotiating team in India.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that despite the uncompromising stands
by the two sides and continued tension on LoC, a fourth Indo-Pak
full-fledged war is not very likely, at least in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Nasim Zehra, a leading columnist, said that "with bilateral
talks deadlocked, the Kargil crisis may take the two countries
towards only a limited war."
</P>
<P>
However, she was of the view that for India, to open fronts
along the international borders "is a very remote possibility."
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sharif has been holding intense discussions with
the army's top brass and close aides to review the deteriorating
situation and evolve Islamabad's operational strategy to deal with
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Military officials are warning against escalation of tensions
between the two uneasy neighbors which have fought three wars, two
of which on Kashmir, since their respective inception in 1947.
</P>
<P>
As the deafening rattle of artillery and mortar fire
continuously reverberates in the sparsely populated areas near the
LoC, the threat of a widening conflict between Pakistan and India
seems to be heightening.
</P>
<P>
There are reports that most of the villages near the Pakistani
side of LoC have been vacated and their inhabitants have moved to
safer places.
</P>
<P>
"There is now a growing and widespread concern that, what has
so far remained a limited military engagement-- confined to Kargil
-- can now spill over and create other theaters of conflict,"
Islamabad-based major English daily The News said editorially.
</P>
<P>
"This must be avoided. A wider conflict is in neither country's
interest," it urged.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here are of the view that in the nuclearized
environment, even a prolonged limited war also held out great
peril.
</P>
<P>
As Prime Minister Sharif said, "it is incumbent on the
leadership to avert any further aggravation which will be
detrimental to the economic development efforts in both
countries."
</P>
<P>
The international community has also urged the two South Asian
nations to restraint and make their best efforts to promote peace
and security through dialogue in pursuance of the Lahore
Declaration signed by the two countries in February this year.
</P>
<P>
One official here said that "statesmanship demands immediate
action to step back from the brink. The consequences of going over
this dangerous precipice are too calamitous to be even
contemplated." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
