<HEADLINE> ADB Loan Used for Tropical Crop Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Zhanjiang State Farm and
Land Reclamation Zone Administration in Guangdong Province, south
China, has completed the building and expansion of two lucrative
sugarcane processing factories and one sisal hemp processing mill
thanks to an Asian Development Bank (ADB) loan.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the ADB signed an agreement with
the Chinese Government in September of 1992 to provide Guangdong
with 55 million U.S. dollars worth of support for tropical crop
development, 25 million dollars of which went to the Zhanjiang
administration.
</P>
<P>
The technological improvement project at the sisal hemp mill
was finished in 1995 and the mill can produce 2,000 tons of yarn
made of sisal fiber annually.
</P>
<P>
The two sugarcane processing factories have a combined
processing capacity of 8,000 tons a year.
</P>
<P>
An appraisal panel of more than 40 specialists from the
Ministry of Agriculture and elsewhere concluded that the three ADB-
financed projects have been a success in the social and economic
benefits during trial operations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
