<HEADLINE> Brazil Gets 150 Million U.S. Dollars in Loan From World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian Finance Minister Pedro
Milan on Wednesday signed an agreement with the World Bank for a
loan of 150 million U.S. dollars to be spent on the second phase
of the country's public health modernization program.
</P>
<P>
Of the sum, Japan's official Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund
will provide 105 million dollars, while other lenders will provide
the rest.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the program, when completed by the end of
2003, will benefit 4.6 million residents in impoverished regions
in the north, northeast and central east of Brazil, by supplying
potable water and sewage systems. 
</P>
