<HEADLINE> U.S. Industrial Production Rises Only 0.2 Percent in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve said
Wednesday that industrial production, making a fragile recovery
from a slump in global demand, edged up 0.2 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
The Fed said the modest production gain at the nation's
factories, mines and utilities reflects a big increase in output
of automotive products, which partially offset a large decline
in the production of appliances.
</P>
<P>
Separately, the beige book, released by the Fed at the same
day, said that consumers are continuing a buying spree,
manufacturing is recovering from a slump in demand overseas and
prices generally remain "well-behaved." But it said with
unemployment at a 29-year low, labor markets remain tight and more
regions are reporting wage pressures that can eventually lead to
inflation.
</P>
<P>
According to the book, the 12 regional Fed banks, while
surveying their areas, reported that the "U.S. economy remains
strong, with gains in activity widespread." 
</P>
</TEXT>
