<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Release of 520 Million Dollars to Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) approved on Wednesday the completion of the seventh review
under Thailand's stand-by arrangement and the disbursement of an
additional 520 million U.S. dollars to Thailand from bilateral and
multilateral sources.
</P>
<P>
This will bring the international community's financial support
for Thailand to 14.1 billion dollars, or more than 80 percent of
the 17.2-billion-dollar financing package approved by the IMF in
August 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Directors (of the IMF) welcomed the continued financial
stability and growing signs of economic recovery in Thailand,"
Shigemitsu Sugisaki, Deputy Managing Director of the IMF, said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's economic growth in 1999 is expected to exceed
projected levels, thanks to the rebounded manufacturing production,
and improved confidence in financial markets, reflected in lower
interest rates, increasing equity values, as well as the return of
capital inflows.
</P>
<P>
The IMF urged the Thai government to fully implement its
stimulus package to underpin the emerging recovery.
</P>
<P>
"Directors encouraged the authorities to continue to implement
fiscal policy flexibly, taking into account the strength of the
recovery. They recommended that spending to bolster the social
safety net should receive an especially high priority, while
maintaining the overall efficiency of budgetary spending,"
Sugisaki said.
</P>
<P>
"Directors emphasized that continued progress in restructuring
corporate debt and in recapitalizing banks remains central to
sustaining economic recovery over the medium term," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
