<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Hold Key to Halting Desertification, Says UNDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Desertification correlates
with poverty and the burden of poverty falls most heavily on
women, said a high-ranking U.N. official on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It is especially appropriate that this year's observance of the
World Day to Combat Desertification takes women's role as its
theme, according to United Nations Development Program (UNDP)
Administrator James Gustave Speth.
</P>
<P>
U.N. data show that an estimated 70 percent of the world's poor
are women.
</P>
<P>
Speth said poverty and its side effects are taking an
increasing toll on the world's drylands, with more than one-third
of world's population living in drylands, which comprise arid,
semiarid and dry subhumid areas.
</P>
<P>
Many of these areas are under siege by environmentally
inadequate farming, urban sprawl, and worsening water shortages.
</P>
<P>
Dryland degradation is vicious circle as poverty drives people
to exploit fragile natural resources for their survival, and the
ensuing environmental decay hurts the poor the most.
</P>
<P>
The poor typically live in marginal areas, which are especially
vulnerable to drought, floods and other calamities.
</P>
<P>
World Day to Combat Desertification, June 17, was proclaimed by
the U.N. General Assembly in 1994.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
