<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0343 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rise Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks rose
sharply Wednesday as investors lessened their worries about
inflation after the government report said U.S. consumer prices
held steady in May.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 189.96 or by 1.7
percent at 10,784.95. The index rose 31.66 points Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The technology
heavy Nasdaq index rose 103.16 or 4.2 percent at 2,517.83,
surpassing the previous record for a one-day point gain of
96.05, set February 11 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose
29.25 at 1,330.41.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department reported that the Consumer Price Index,
excluding the volatile energy and food categories, rose 0.1
percent in May, triggering a buying spree on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
A surge of 0.7 percent in April Consumer Price Index sparked
fears about inflation and the Federal Reserve warned it would
raise interest rates to cool off the economy if inflation was
building up in the economy, thus dragging the stock market down.
</P>
<P>
But some economists said the low consumer prices in May
did not quell speculation about higher interest rates because
the Federal Reserve may consider other developments such as
higher global demand for U.S. goods following the economic
recovery overseas, which could push up prices in the coming
months.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 9.89 at 632.17 and the
American Stock Exchange index rose 1.00 at 764.92. The Russell
2000 index of smaller companies rose 7.19 at 441.20.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 13-to-7 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,998 up, 1,055 down and
510 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 796.86 million shares from 693.10
million in the previous session.  
</P>
</TEXT>
