<HEADLINE> Russia Sees KLA Status in Kosovo Illegal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A senior Russian diplomat
said here Wednesday that the 15-nation U.N. Security Council
needed to deal with the refusal of the rebel Kosovo Liberation
Army (KLA) to disarm, an obvious violation of a key U.N.
resolution on the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Sergey Lavrov, Russian permanent representative to the United
Nations, told reporters after a closed-door Security Council
meeting that NATO troops stood by as KLA guerrillas moved into
positions, contrary to an omnibus resolution approving a Kosovo
peace plan last week.
</P>
<P>
He said that if the KLA reported movement is confirmed, "it is
a violation of the resolution and something must be done about
it."
</P>
<P>
"We are concerned by the media reports that as Serbs withdraw
according to schedule and to everybody's satisfaction, the KLA
moves in and takes positions and refuses to demilitarize and
basically makes statement publicly that they would be running the
area and not anybody else," Lavrov said.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, adopted on June 10, approved an international
force to ensure the safe return of nearly a million ethnic
Albanian refugees and listed as its duties the "demilitarization"
of the KLA, ethnic Albanian guerrillas who have been fighting for
independence from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
KLA leaders have said that they would not disarm until the
Russian troops, who have taken position in the airport in
Pristina, capital of Kosovo Province, join a unified NATO
command.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and Russian officials are meeting in Helsinki to try and
break a deadlock over Moscow's role in the Kosovo peacekeeping
force, knows as KFOR. Russia, who helps mediate an end to the NATO
air strikes, is seeking its own separate sector in Kosovo
peacekeeping operations, rather than work under NATO command and
send some 200 soldiers over the weekend to occupy Pristina
airport.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
