<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. High School Students Say "No" to Teaching Career </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 16 (Xinhua) -- High school students in the United
States may not help ease the country's projected shortage of 2.2
million teachers over the next decade, according to a report released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a nationwide poll sponsored by the Milken Family Foundation, 55
percent of the students say that they have "little' or "no interest at
all" in a career in teaching, citing school safety as the main
drawback, followed closely by the poor image and lack of respect for
teachers and low salaries.
</P>
<P>
"These findings underscore the daunting challenge the nation faces
in meeting the projected teacher shortage," said Santa Monica,
California-based foundation.
</P>
<P>
The lack of interest in teaching was particularly pronounced among
African-Americans and boys, respectively 68 percent and 62 percent of
whom expressed little or no interest. Only 14 percent of students
overall expressed "a great deal of interest" in teaching.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 42 percent of older Americans nearing retirement age
might consider a teaching career if certification and training
barriers were eased, according to a separate survey also sponsored by
the foundation.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of tragic shootings in Colorado and Georgia, 70
percent of the high school students and 76 percent of older
Americans cite school safety as a major drawback. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
