<DOCNO> XIE19990617.0346 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ireland To Scrap Alcohol-free "Holy Hour" - Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Ireland looks ready to scrap its
traditionally dry "Holy Hour" with the announcement of a
government-backed Intoxicating Liquor Bill, a Reuters report said
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bill would scrap Sunday afternoon closing rules in a
country which is better known for alcohol consumption than
abstinence. It was expected that the bill would lift a bar on
extended drinking hours on a Saturday night and allow once-off
all-night opening for New Year's Eve to mark the millennium.
</P>
<P>
Irish Justice Minister John O'Donoghue said in a statement he
hoped to bring the bill before parliament very soon so it could be
approved before the summer recess.
</P>
<P>
The short Bill was being drafted immediately to facilitate the
tourist industry over this summer's tourist and holiday season,
the report quoted the department as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ireland, an overwhelmingly Roman Catholic country, has up to
now observed Sunday afternoon closing, though many bars and public
houses reopen later in the day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
